{"title_page": "John Brecknock", "text_new": "[[File:John-Brecknock-as-Werther.png|thumb|upright|alt=black and white photograph of white man, clean shaven in 19th century costume, looking pensive|Brecknock in the title role of ''[[Werther]]'']] \n'''John Leighton Brecknock''' (29 November 1937 \u2013 30 May 2017) was an English [[opera]]tic [[tenor]]. He was born at [[Long Eaton]], Derbyshire, joined the chorus of [[English National Opera|Sadler's Wells Opera]] in 1967 and graduated to small solo roles.<ref name=dt/> He made his [[The Royal Opera|Covent Garden]] debut in 1974 as Fenton in [[Giuseppe Verdi|Verdi]]'s ''[[Falstaff (opera)|Falstaff]]'' with [[Tito Gobbi]]. In 1977 he co-starred at the [[Paris Op\u00e9ra]] with [[Teresa Berganza]] in [[Gioachino Rossini|Rossini's]] ''[[La Cenerentola]]'', and in 1978 sang Don Ottavio in [[Mozart]]'s ''[[Don Giovanni]]'' at the [[Metropolitan Opera]], New York, to the Donna Anna of [[Joan Sutherland]], who wrote of his \"beautiful glossy voice and easy technique\".<ref name=dt/> In London he performed at [[English National Opera]], the [[The Royal Opera|Royal Opera]] and [[the Proms]].<ref name=dt>\"John Brecknock: Tenor with the ENO known for his 'beautiful glossy voice\", ''The Daily Telegraph'', 16 June 2017, p. 29</ref>\n\nAmong Brecknock's Mozart roles were the Speaker in ''[[The Magic Flute]]'',<ref>Sadie, Stanley. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9Vnh63 \"Mackerras's serene, glowing Mozart\"], ''The Times'', 24 April 1969, p. 15</ref> Ferrando in ''[[Cos\u00ec fan tutte]]''<ref>Blyth, Alan. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9Vni32 \"A model comedy\"] ''The Times'', 26 March 1970, p. 14</ref> and  Belmonte in ''[[Die Entf\u00fchrung aus dem Serail|The Seraglio]]''.<ref>Mann, William. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9VnkR5 \"The Seraglio\"], ''The Times'', 29 July 1971, p. 9</ref> In the Italian repertoire, his roles included Alfredo in ''[[La traviata]]'',<ref>Mann, William. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9VnjQ8 \"Vivid rhythm\"']. ''The Times'', 25 September 1970, p. 8</ref> the Count in ''[[The Barber of Seville]]'',<ref>Elvin, Ren\u00e9. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/44201294 \"Lettre de Londres\"], ''La Nouvelle Revue des Deux Mondes'', February 1981, p. 486</ref> Rinuccio in ''[[Gianni Schicchi]]''<ref>[http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?performance=15133&row=1&searchtype=workprodperf&person=John%20Brecknock \"Gianni Schicchi\"], Royal Opera House Performance Archive. Retrieved 18 March 2019</ref> and the title role in ''[[Le comte Ory|Count Ory]]''.<ref>Sadie, Stanley. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9Vnm7X \"Fine musical wit\"], ''The Times'', 19 February 1972, p. 9</ref> Among his roles in French operas were the title role in ''[[Werther]]'',<ref>Elvin, Ren\u00e9. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/44201380 \"Lettre de Londres\"], ''La Nouvelle Revue des Deux Mondes'', May 1977, p. 492</ref> Iopas in ''[[Les Troyens]]'',<ref>[http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?performance=12135&row=2&searchtype=workprodperf&person=John%20Brecknock \"The Trojans at Carthage\"] Royal Opera House Performance Archive. Retrieved 18 March 2019</ref> Romeo in ''[[Rom\u00e9o et Juliette|Romeo and Juliet]]'',<ref>Mann, William. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9VnquX \"Romeo and Juliet\"] ''The Times'', 15 January 1981, p. 11</ref> Des Grieux in ''[[Manon]]''<ref>Higgins, John. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9Vnsd1 \"Opera\"], ''The Times'', 26 February 1982, p. 13</ref> and B\u00e9n\u00e9dict in ''[[B\u00e9atrice et B\u00e9n\u00e9dict]]''.<ref>Finch, Hilary. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9Vnvy1 \"Opera\"], ''The Times'', 25 May 1983, p. 10.</ref>\n\nBrecknock's repertoire included several [[op\u00e9ra comique|op\u00e9ras comiques]] and operettas. His [[Jacques Offenbach|Offenbach]] roles included the title characters in ''[[Barbe-bleue (opera)|Bluebeard]]'' and ''[[Robinson Cruso\u00e9|Robinson Crusoe]]'',<ref>Chissell, Joan. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9VnhV2. Retrieved 18 March 2019 \"Return of Bluebeard\"], ''The Times'', 12 November 1969, p. 14; and [http://www.jstor.org/stable/961180 \"Music in London\"], ''The Musical Times'', October 1980, pp. 644\u2013646</ref> Paris in ''[[La belle H\u00e9l\u00e8ne]]'',<ref>Mann, William. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9Vnny3 \"La belle H\u00e9l\u00e8ne],\" ''The Times'', 5 September. 1975, p. 7</ref> and Pluto in ''[[Orpheus in the Underworld]]''.<ref>Higgins, John. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9Vnzy3 \"Hell for leather\"], ''The Times'', 12 February 1988, p. 16</ref> In [[Gilbert and Sullivan]] he sang the Defendant in ''[[Trial by Jury]]'',<ref>[http://www.jstor.org/stable/963274,\"London Diary for August\"], ''The Musical Times'', July 1982, pp. 518\u2013519</ref> and Tolloller in ''[[Iolanthe]]''.<ref>Sadie, Stanley. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9VngT3 \"A spirited Iolanthe\"]''The Times'', 3 April 1969, p. 14</ref>\n\nIn less-frequently performed operas Brecknock's roles included the Page in [[Claudio Monteverdi|Monteverdi's]] ''[[L'incoronazione di Poppea|The Coronation of Poppea]]'',<ref>Mann, William. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9Vnkh5 \"The Coronation of Poppea\"], ''The Times'', 25 November 1971, p. 20</ref> Jupiter in [[George Frideric Handel|Handel's]] ''[[Semele (Handel)|Semele]]'',<ref>[http://www.jstor.org/stable/957238 \"Sadler's Wells Opera\"], ''The Musical Times'', October 1970, p. 991</ref> and Adriano in [[Giacomo Meyerbeer|Meyerbeer's]] ''[[Il crociato in Egitto]]''.<ref>Klein, John W. [http://www.jstor.org/stable/957622 \"Meyerbeer and 'Il Crociato'\"], ''The Musical Times'', January 1972, p. 40</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brecknock, John}}\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:English opera singers]]\n[[Category:English tenors]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:John-Brecknock-as-Werther.png|thumb|upright|alt=black and white photograph of white man, clean shaven in 19th century costume, looking pensive|Brecknock in the title role of ''[[Werther]]'']] \n'''John Leighton Brecknock''' (29 November 1937 \u2013 30 May 2017) was an English [[opera]]tic [[tenor]]. He was born at [[Long Eaton]], Derbyshire, joined the chorus of [[English National Opera|Sadler's Wells Opera]] in 1967 and graduated to small solo roles.<ref name=dt/> He made his [[The Royal Opera|Covent Garden]] debut in 1974 as Fenton in [[Giuseppe Verdi|Verdi]]'s ''[[Falstaff (opera)|Falstaff]]'' with [[Tito Gobbi]]. In 1977 he co-starred at the [[Paris Op\u00e9ra]] with [[Teresa Berganza]] in [[Gioachino Rossini|Rossini's]] ''[[La Cenerentola]]'', and in 1978 sang Don Ottavio in [[Mozart]]'s ''[[Don Giovanni]]'' at the [[Metropolitan Opera]], New York, to the Donna Anna of [[Joan Sutherland]], who wrote of his \"beautiful glossy voice and easy technique\".<ref name=dt/> In London he performed at [[English National Opera]], the [[The Royal Opera|Royal Opera]] and [[the Proms]].<ref name=dt>\"John Brecknock: Tenor with the ENO known for his 'beautiful glossy voice\", ''The Daily Telegraph'', 16 June 2017, p. 29</ref> \n\nAmong Brecknock's Mozart roles were the Speaker in ''[[The Magic Flute]]'',<ref>Sadie, Stanley. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9Vnh63 \"Mackerras's serene, glowing Mozart\"], ''The Times'', 24 April 1969, p. 15</ref> Ferrando in ''[[Cos\u00ec fan tutte]]''<ref>Blyth, Alan. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9Vni32 \"A model comedy\"] ''The Times'', 26 March 1970, p. 14</ref> and  Belmonte in ''[[Die Entf\u00fchrung aus dem Serail|The Seraglio]]''.<ref>Mann, William. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9VnkR5 \"The Seraglio\"], ''The Times'', 29 July 1971, p. 9</ref> In the Italian repertoire, his roles included Alfredo in ''[[La traviata]]'',<ref>Mann, William. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9VnjQ8 \"Vivid rhythm\"']. ''The Times'', 25 September 1970, p. 8</ref> the Count in ''[[The Barber of Seville]]'',<ref> Elvin, Ren\u00e9. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/44201294 \"Lettre de Londres\"], ''La Nouvelle Revue des Deux Mondes'', February 1981, p. 486</ref> Rinuccio in ''[[Gianni Schicchi]]''<ref>[http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?performance=15133&row=1&searchtype=workprodperf&person=John%20Brecknock \"Gianni Schicchi\"], Royal Opera House Performance Archive. Retrieved 18 March 2019</ref> and the title role in ''[[Le comte Ory|Count Ory]]''.<ref>Sadie, Stanley. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9Vnm7X \"Fine musical wit\"], ''The Times'', 19 February 1972, p. 9</ref> Among his roles in French operas were the title role in ''[[Werther]]'',<ref>Elvin, Ren\u00e9. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/44201380 \"Lettre de Londres\"], ''La Nouvelle Revue des Deux Mondes'', May 1977, p. 492</ref> Iopas in ''[[Les Troyens]]'',<ref>[http://www.rohcollections.org.uk/performance.aspx?performance=12135&row=2&searchtype=workprodperf&person=John%20Brecknock \"The Trojans at Carthage\"] Royal Opera House Performance Archive. Retrieved 18 March 2019</ref> Romeo in ''[[Rom\u00e9o et Juliette|Romeo and Juliet]]'',<ref>Mann, William. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9VnquX \"Romeo and Juliet\"] ''The Times'', 15 January 1981, p. 11</ref> Des Grieux in ''[[Manon]]''<ref>Higgins, John. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9Vnsd1 \"Opera\"], ''The Times'', 26 February 1982, p. 13</ref> and B\u00e9n\u00e9dict in ''[[B\u00e9atrice et B\u00e9n\u00e9dict]]''.<ref>Finch, Hilary. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9Vnvy1 \"Opera\"], ''The Times'', 25 May 1983, p. 10.</ref>\n\nBrecknock's repertoire included several [[op\u00e9ra comique|op\u00e9ras comiques]] and operettas. His [[Jacques Offenbach|Offenbach]] roles included the title characters in ''[[Barbe-bleue (opera)|Bluebeard]]'' and ''[[Robinson Cruso\u00e9|Robinson Crusoe]]'',<ref>Chissell, Joan. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9VnhV2. Retrieved 18 March 2019 \"Return of Bluebeard\"], ''The Times'', 12 November 1969, p. 14; and [http://www.jstor.org/stable/961180 \"Music in London\"], ''The Musical Times'', October 1980, pp. 644\u2013646</ref> Paris in ''[[La belle H\u00e9l\u00e8ne]]'',<ref>Mann, William. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9Vnny3 \"La belle H\u00e9l\u00e8ne],\" ''The Times'', 5 September. 1975, p. 7</ref> and Pluto in ''[[Orpheus in the Underworld]]''.<ref>Higgins, John. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9Vnzy3 \"Hell for leather\"], ''The Times'', 12 February 1988, p. 16</ref> In [[Gilbert and Sullivan]] he sang the Defendant in ''[[Trial by Jury]]'',<ref>[http://www.jstor.org/stable/963274,\"London Diary for August\"], ''The Musical Times'', July 1982, pp. 518\u2013519</ref> and Tolloller in ''[[Iolanthe]]''.<ref>Sadie, Stanley. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9VngT3 \"A spirited Iolanthe\"]''The Times'', 3 April 1969, p. 14</ref> \n\nIn less-frequently performed operas Brecknock's roles included the Page in [[Claudio Monteverdi|Monteverdi's]] ''[[L'incoronazione di Poppea|The Coronation of Poppea]]'',<ref>Mann, William. [http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/9Vnkh5 \"The Coronation of Poppea\"], ''The Times'', 25 November 1971, p. 20</ref> Jupiter in [[George Frideric Handel|Handel's]] ''[[Semele (Handel)|Semele]]'',<ref>[http://www.jstor.org/stable/957238 \"Sadler's Wells Opera\"], ''The Musical Times'', October 1970, p. 991</ref> and Adriano in [[Giacomo Meyerbeer|Meyerbeer's]] ''[[Il crociato in Egitto]]''.<ref>Klein, John W. [http://www.jstor.org/stable/957622 \"Meyerbeer and 'Il Crociato'\"], ''The Musical Times'', January 1972, p. 40</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brecknock, John}}\n\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:English opera singers]]\n[[Category:English tenors]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Brecknock"}
{"title_page": "Medical tourism", "text_new": "'''Medical tourism''' refers to people traveling abroad to obtain medical treatment. In the past, this usually referred to those who traveled from less-developed countries to major medical centers in highly developed countries for treatment unavailable at home.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Horowitz|first1=Michael D.|last2=Rosensweig|first2=Jeffrey A.|last3=Jones|first3=Christopher A.|year=2007|title=Medical Tourism: Globalization of the Healthcare Marketplace|journal=MedGenMed|volume=9|issue=4|page=33|pmc=2234298|pmid=18311383}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.nchu.edu.tw/pweb/users/hychuo/lesson/5877.pdf|title=Medical tourism--health care in the global economy|publisher=Physician Exec|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> However, in recent years it may equally refer to those from developed countries who travel to developing countries for lower-priced medical treatments. The motivation may be also for medical services unavailable or non-licensed in the home country: There are differences between the medical agencies (FDA, EMA etc.) world-wide, whether a drug is approved in their country or not. Even within Europe, although therapy protocols might be approved by the European Medical Agency (EMA), several countries have their own review organizations (i.e. NICE by the NHS) in order to evaluate whether the same therapy protocol would be \"cost-effective\", so that patients face differences in the therapy protocols, particularly in the access of these drugs, which might be partially explained by the financial strength of the particular Health System.\n\nMedical tourism most often is for [[surgery|surgeries]] (cosmetic or otherwise) or similar treatments, though people also travel for [[dental tourism]] or [[fertility tourism]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wordspy.com/words/fertilitytourism.asp|title=fertility tourism|author=Paul McFedries|date=2006-05-17|publisher=Word Spy|accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref> People with rare conditions may travel to countries where the treatment is better understood. However, almost all types of health care are available, including [[psychiatry]], alternative medicine, convalescent care, and even burial services.\n\nHealth tourism is a wider term for travel that focuses on medical treatments and the use of healthcare services. It covers a wide field of health-oriented, tourism ranging from preventive and health-conductive treatment to rehabilitational and curative forms of travel. [[Wellness tourism]] is a related field.\n\n==History==\nThe first recorded instance of people travelling for medical treatment dates back thousands of years to when [[Greeks|Greek]] pilgrims traveled from the eastern [[Mediterranean]] to a small area in the [[Saronic Gulf]] called [[Epidauria]].<ref>{{cite web|title=History of Medical Tourism|url=http://www.discovermedicaltourism.com/history/|website=Discovermedicaltourism.com|publisher=Discovermedicaltourism.com|accessdate=2015-11-03}}</ref> This territory was the sanctuary of the healing god [[Asklepios]].\n\n[[Spa town]]s and [[sanatorium|sanitaria]] were early forms of medical tourism. In 18th-century Europe patients visited spas because they were places with supposedly health-giving [[mineral water]]s, treating diseases from [[gout]] to [[liver]] disorders and [[bronchitis]].<ref name=\"Gahlinger2008\">Gahlinger, PM. The Medical Tourism Travel Guide: Your Complete Reference to Top-Quality, Low-Cost Dental, Cosmetic, Medical Care & Surgery Overseas. Sunrise River Press, 2008</ref>\n\n==Description==\nFactors that have led to the increasing popularity of medical travel include the high cost of health care, long wait times for certain procedures, the ease and affordability of international travel, and improvements in both technology and standards of care in many countries.<ref name=\"Goering March 28, 2008\">Laurie Goering, [http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chi-medical-tourism_goeringmar28,0,4555735.story  \"For big surgery, Delhi is dealing,\"] The ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', March 28, 2008  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080401041824/http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chi-medical-tourism_goeringmar28%2C0%2C4555735.story |date=April 1, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Tompkins|first1=Olga|title=Medical Tourism|journal=AAOHN Journal|date=2010|volume=58|issue=1|page=40|doi=10.3928/08910162-20091223-04|pmid=20102121}}</ref>  The avoidance of waiting times is the leading factor for medical tourism from the UK, whereas in the US, the main reason is cheaper prices abroad. Furthermore, death rates even in the developed countries differ extremely, i.e. UK versus seven other leading countries, including the US.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2013/sep/12/hospital-death-rates-england-higher-us|title=Hospital death rates in England 45% higher than in US, report finds|last=Ramesh|first=Randeep|date=2013-09-12|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-03-17|last2=editor|first2=social affairs|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nMany surgical procedures performed in medical tourism destinations cost a fraction of the price they do in other countries. For example, in the United States, a liver transplant that may cost $300,000 USD, would generally cost about $91,000 USD in Taiwan.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2004023,00.html | work=Time | first=Sarah | last=Tung | title=Is Taiwan Asia's Next One-Stop Plastic-Surgery Shop? | date=July 16, 2010}}</ref> A large draw to medical travel is convenience and speed. Countries that operate public health-care systems often have long wait times for certain operations, for example, an estimated 782,936 Canadian patients spent an average waiting time of 9.4 weeks on medical waiting lists in 2005.<ref>[http://www.fraserinstitute.org/Commerce.Web/product_files/PrivateCostofPublicQueues2005.pdf The Private Cost of Public Queues in 2005]{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[Fraser Institute]]</ref> Canada has also set waiting time benchmarks for non-urgent medical procedures, including a 26-week waiting period for a hip replacement and a 16-week wait for cataract surgery.<ref>[http://www.canada.com/Wait+times+shorter+some+medical+procedures+report/1528971/story.html Wait times shorter for some medical procedures: report.], [[Canwest News Service]]</ref>\n\nIn First World countries such as the United States, medical tourism has large growth prospects and potentially destabilizing implications.  A forecast by [[Deloitte Consulting]] published in August 2008 projected that medical tourism originating in the US could jump by a factor of ten over the next decade.  An estimated 750,000 Americans went abroad for health care in 2007, and the report estimated that 1.5 million would seek health care outside the US in 2008.  The growth in medical tourism has the potential to cost US health care providers billions of dollars in lost revenue.<ref>Linda A. Johnson, [http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2008/08/03/BUGA121GPF.DTL&type=health \"Americans look abroad to save on health care: Medical tourism could jump tenfold in next decade,\"] The [[San Francisco Chronicle]], August 3, 2008</ref>\n\nAn authority at the [[Harvard Business School]] stated that \"medical tourism is promoted much more heavily in the United Kingdom than in the United States\".<ref>Lagace, Martha [http://hbswk.hbs.edu/item/5814.html \"The Rise of Medical Tourism\"], Harvard Business School Working Knowledge, December 17, 2007. Retrieved July 1, 2008.</ref>\n\nAdditionally, some patients in some First World countries are finding that insurance either does not cover orthopedic surgery (such as knee or hip replacement) or limits the choice of the facility, surgeon, or prosthetics to be used.\n\nPopular medical travel worldwide destinations include: [[Canada]], [[Cuba]], [[Costa Rica]], [[Ecuador]], [[India]], [[Israel]], [[Jordan]], [[Malaysia]], [[Mexico]], [[Singapore]], [[South Korea]], [[Taiwan]], [[Thailand]], [[Turkey]], [[United States]].<ref>[http://www.patientsbeyondborders.com/medical-tourism-statistics-facts \"Patient Beyond Borders, Medical Tourism Facts&Statistics\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426234639/http://www.patientsbeyondborders.com/medical-tourism-statistics-facts |date=2014-04-26 }} Retrieved July 14, 2014</ref>\n\nPopular destinations for cosmetic surgery include: [[Argentina]], [[Bolivia]], [[Brazil]], [[Colombia]], [[Costa Rica]], [[Cuba]], [[Ecuador]], [[Mexico]], [[Turkey]], [[Thailand]] and [[Ukraine]]. According to the \"Sociedad Boliviana de Cirugia Plastica y Reconstructiva\", more than 70% of middle and upper class women in the country have had some form of plastic surgery. Other destination countries include [[Belgium]], [[Poland]], [[Slovakia]] and [[South Africa]].<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/healthcare/medicaltourism.html \"Medical tourism: Need surgery, will travel\"] ''CBC News Online'', June 18, 2004. Retrieved September 5, 2006.</ref>\n\nSome people travel for [[assisted reproductive technology|assisted pregnancy]], such as [[in-vitro fertilization]], or [[surrogate pregnancy|surrogacy]],<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Jones CA, Keith LG | year = 2006 | title = Medical tourism and reproductive outsourcing: the dawning of a new paradigm for healthcare | url = | journal = Int J Fertil Womens Med | volume = 51 | issue = | pages = 251\u2013255 }}</ref> or freezing embryos for retro-production.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Jones C | year = 2007 | title = Ethical and legal conundrums of post-modern procreation | url = | journal = Int J Gynaecol Obstet | volume =  | issue = | page =  }}</ref>\n\nHowever, perceptions of medical tourism are not always positive. In places like the US, which has high standards of quality, medical tourism is viewed as risky. In some parts of the world, wider political issues can influence where medical tourists will choose to seek out health care.\n\n[[Medical tourism provider]]s have developed as intermediaries which unite potential medical tourists with surgeons, provider hospitals and other organizations. In some cases, surgeons from the United States have  signed up with medical tourism providers to travel to Mexico  to treat American patients. The hope is that using an American surgeon may alleviate concerns about going outside the country, and persuade self-insured American employers to offer this cost-effective option to their workers as a way to save money while still provide high-quality care.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Galewitz |first1=Phil |title=To Save Money, American Patients And Surgeons Meet In Cancun |url=https://khn.org/news/to-save-money-american-patients-and-surgeons-meet-in-cancun/ |website=Kaiser Health News |publisher=Kaiser Family Foundation |accessdate=14 August 2019|date=2019-08-12 }}</ref> Companies that focus on medical value travel typically provide nurse case managers to assist patients with pre- and post-travel medical issues. They may also help provide resources for follow-up care upon the patient's return.\n\nCircumvention tourism is also an area of medical tourism that has grown. Circumvention tourism is travel in order to access medical services that are legal in the destination country but illegal in the home country. This can include travel for fertility treatments that aren\u2019t yet approved in the home country, abortion, and doctor-assisted suicide.<ref name=\"Circumvention Tourism\">{{cite journal|last1=Cohen|first1=Glenn|title=Circumvention Tourism|journal=Cornell Law Review|date=2012|volume=97|issue=1309}}</ref> Abortion tourism can be found most commonly in Europe, where travel between countries is relatively simple. Ireland and Poland, two European countries with highly restrictive abortion laws, have the highest rates of circumvention tourism. In Poland especially, it is estimated that each year nearly 7,000 women travel to the UK, where abortion services are free through the National Health Service.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Day|first1=Matthew|title=Polish women encouraged to come to UK for 'free abortions' on NHS|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/poland/7441990/Polish-women-encouraged-to-come-to-UK-for-free-abortions-on-NHS.html|accessdate=28 April 2015|agency=The Telegraph|publisher=Telegraph Media Group|date=March 15, 2010}}</ref> There are also efforts being made by independent organizations and doctors, such as with Women on Waves, to help women circumvent draconian laws in order to access medical services. With Women on Waves, the organization uses a mobile clinic aboard a ship to provide medical abortions in international waters, where the law of the country whose flag is flown applies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ship campaigns|url=http://www.womenonwaves.org/en/page/2582/ship-campaigns|website=Women on Waves|publisher=Women on Waves}}</ref>\n\n==International healthcare accreditation==\n{{Main|International healthcare accreditation}}\n\nInternational healthcare accreditation is the process of certifying a level of quality for healthcare providers and programs across multiple countries.  [[List of international healthcare accreditation organizations|International healthcare accreditation organizations]] certify a wide range of healthcare programs such as hospitals, primary care centers, medical transport, and ambulatory care services.<ref>{{citation|title=Joint Commission International Accreditation & Certificationweb |url=http://www.jointcommissioninternational.org/Accreditation-and-Certification-Process/ |publisher=Joint Commission International |accessdate=19 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722144022/http://www.jointcommissioninternational.org/Accreditation-and-Certification-Process/ |archivedate=22 July 2011 }}</ref>  There are a number of accreditation schemes available based in a number of different countries around the world.\n\nThe oldest international accrediting body is Accreditation Canada, formerly known as the Canadian Council on Health Services Accreditation,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.accreditation.ca/about-us/history/ |title=Accreditation Canada History |accessdate=June 12, 2012}}</ref> which accredited the Bermuda Hospital Board as soon as 1968.  Since then, it has accredited hospitals and health service organizations in ten other countries.\n[[File:GoldSeal 4color.jpg|alt=JCI Gold Seal, an example of international hospital standard accreditation|thumb|JCI Gold Seal, an example of international hospital standard \naccreditation\n]]\nIn the United States, the accreditation group [[Joint Commission International]] (JCI) was formed in 1994 to provide international clients education and consulting services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncamss.org/AnnualMtg2009/Dengler%20-%20Joint%20Commission%20History.pdf|title=A Journal Through the History of The Joint Commission|publisher=The Joint Commission|accessdate=2014-04-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413150707/http://www.ncamss.org/AnnualMtg2009/Dengler%20-%20Joint%20Commission%20History.pdf|archive-date=2014-04-13|url-status=dead}}</ref> Many international hospitals today see obtaining international accreditation as a way to attract American patients.<ref>[http://www.medicaltravelauthority.com/Medical-Tourism-Magazine-Issue-2.pdf \"Medical Tourism Magazine\"], Medical Tourism Association, February 2008</ref>\n\nJoint Commission International is a relative of the Joint Commission in the United States. Both are US-style independent private sector not-for-profit organizations that develop nationally and internationally recognized procedures and standards to help improve patient care and safety. They work with hospitals to help them meet Joint Commission standards for patient care and then accredit those hospitals meeting the standards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jointcommission.org/AboutUs/Fact_Sheets/jci_facts.htm |title=Facts about Joint Commission International |publisher=Joint Commission |date=2008-12-11 |accessdate=2010-09-15}}</ref>\n\nA British scheme, QHA Trent Accreditation, is an active independent holistic accreditation scheme, as well as GCR.org which monitors the success metrics and standards of almost 500,000 medical clinics worldwide.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=G-jECQAAQBAJ&pg=PA378&lpg=PA378&dq=qha+trent+accreditation#v=onepage&q=qha%20trent%20accreditation&f=false|title=Handbook on Medical Tourism and Patient Mobility|date=2015|isbn=9781783471195|last1=Lunt|first1=Neil|last2=Horsfall|first2=Daniel|last3=Hanefeld|first3=Johanna}}</ref>\n\nThe different international healthcare accreditation schemes vary in quality, size, cost, intent and the skill and intensity of their marketing. They also vary in terms of cost to hospitals and healthcare institutions making use of them.<ref>[https://archive.is/20130126134030/http://www.imtjonline.com/news/india-accreditation-a-must \"INDIA: Accreditation a must\"], International Medical Travel Journal</ref>\n\nIncreasingly, some hospitals are looking towards dual international accreditation, perhaps having both JCI to cover potential US clientele, and Accreditation Canada or QHA Trent. As a result of competition between clinics for American medical tourists, there have been initiatives to rank hospitals based on patient-reported metrics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldhospitalmonitor.com |title=Home |publisher=World Hospital Monitor |accessdate=2010-09-15}}</ref>\n\n==Risks==\nMedical tourism carries some risks that locally provided medical care either does not carry or carries to a much lesser degree.\n\nSome countries, such as South Africa, or Thailand have very different infectious disease-related epidemiology to Europe and North America. Exposure to diseases without having built up natural immunity can be a hazard for weakened individuals, specifically with respect to gastrointestinal diseases (e.g. [[hepatitis A]], [[amoebic dysentery]], [[paratyphoid]]) which could weaken progress and expose the patient to [[Mosquito-borne disease|mosquito-transmitted diseases]], [[influenza]], and [[tuberculosis]]. However, because in poor tropical nations diseases run the gamut, doctors seem to be more open to the possibility of considering any infectious disease, including [[HIV]], TB, and [[typhoid]], while there are cases in the West where patients were consistently misdiagnosed for years because such diseases are perceived to be \"rare\" in the West.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lungil.org/il/copd/TBMisdiagnosed.asp|title=TB Often Misdiagnosed|publisher=American Lung Association of Illinois|accessdate=2007-03-10 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070301064539/http://www.lungil.org/il/copd/TBMisdiagnosed.asp |archivedate = March 1, 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe quality of post-operative care can also vary dramatically, depending on the hospital and country, and may be different from US or European standards. Also, traveling long distances soon after surgery can increase the risk of complications. Long flights and decreased mobility associated with window seats can predispose one towards developing [[deep vein thrombosis]] and potentially a [[pulmonary embolism]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chestnet.org/accp/article/new-dvt-guidelines-no-evidence-support-economy-class-syndrome |title=New DVT Guidelines: No Evidence to Support \"Economy Class Syndrome\"; Oral Contraceptives, Sitting in a Window Seat, Advanced Age, and Pregnancy Increase DVT Risk in Long-distance Travelers |date=7 February 2012 |publisher=American College of Chest Physicians |accessdate=10 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120209195940/http://www.chestnet.org/accp/article/new-dvt-guidelines-no-evidence-support-economy-class-syndrome |archive-date=9 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Other vacation activities can be problematic as well &mdash; for example, scars may become darker and more noticeable if they are sunburned while healing.<ref>[http://familydoctor.org/familydoctor/en/prevention-wellness/staying-healthy/first-aid/caring-for-your-incision-after-surgery.html \"Caring for Your Incision After Surgery\"], FamilyDoctor.org, ''American Academy of Family Physicians'', December 2010. Retrieved July 23, 2013.</ref>\n\nAlso, health facilities treating medical tourists may lack an adequate complaints policy to deal appropriately and fairly with complaints made by dissatisfied patients.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pat.nhs.uk/downloads/ComplaintsleafletDec2011.pdf |title=Compliments, Comments, Concerns or Complaints |publisher=The Pennine Acute Hospitals |accessdate=2015-01-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150101195543/http://www.pat.nhs.uk/downloads/ComplaintsleafletDec2011.pdf |archive-date=2015-01-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nDifferences in healthcare provider standards around the world have been recognised by the [[World Health Organization]], and in 2004 it launched the [[World Alliance for Patient Safety]]. This body assists hospitals and government around the world in setting patient safety policy and practices that can become particularly relevant when providing medical tourism services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/patientsafety/en/ |title=World Alliance for Patient Safety |publisher=Who.int |date=2010-05-05 |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref>\n\nPatients traveling to countries with less stringent surgical standards may be at higher risk for complications.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cusumano|first=Lucas R.|last2=Tran|first2=Vivy|last3=Tlamsa|first3=Aileen|last4=Chung|first4=Philip|last5=Grossberg|first5=Robert|last6=Weston|first6=Gregory|last7=Sarwar|first7=Uzma N.|date=October 2017|title=Rapidly growing Mycobacterium infections after cosmetic surgery in medical tourists: the Bronx experience and a review of the literature|journal=International Journal of Infectious Diseases |volume=63|pages=1\u20136|doi=10.1016/j.ijid.2017.07.022|issn=1878-3511|pmid=28780185}}</ref> If there are complications, the patient may need to stay in the foreign country for longer than planned or if they have returned home, will not have easy access to follow up care.<ref name=\"Ginger Rough\">{{cite news|url=http://www.azcentral.com/arizonarepublic/news/articles/2009/06/07/20090607rxtourism0607.html?nclick_check=1#reply17699291|title=Globe-trotting to cut down on medical costs|last=Ginger Rough|date=June 7, 2009|work=[[The Arizona Republic]]|accessdate=1 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nPatients sometimes travel to another country to obtain medical procedures that doctors in their home country refuse to perform because they believed that the risks of the procedure outweigh the benefits. Such patients may have difficulty getting insurance (whether public or private) to cover follow up medical costs should the feared complications indeed arise.\n\n===Legal issues===\nReceiving medical care abroad may subject medical tourists to unfamiliar legal issues.<ref name=\"AHC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ahcpub.com/hot_topics/?htid=1&httid=1874 |title=Medical Tourism: Ethical Pitfalls of Seeking Health Care Overseas |publisher=Ahcpub.com |accessdate=2011-10-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707094359/http://www.ahcpub.com/hot_topics/?htid=1&httid=1874 |archive-date=2011-07-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The limited nature of [[litigation]] in various countries is a reason for accessibility of care overseas. While some countries currently presenting themselves as attractive medical tourism destinations provide some form of legal remedies for [[medical malpractice]], these legal avenues may be unappealing to the medical tourist. Should problems arise, patients might not be covered by adequate personal insurance or might be unable to seek compensation via [[malpractice]] lawsuits. Hospitals and/or doctors in some countries may be unable to pay the financial damages awarded by a court to a patient who has sued them, owing to the hospital and/or the doctor not possessing appropriate insurance cover and/or medical indemnity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medicalprotection.org/uk |title=Medical Protection Society &#124; MPS UK |publisher=Medicalprotection.org |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref>\n\nIssues can also arise for patients who seek out services that are illegal in their home country. In this case, some countries have the jurisdiction to prosecute their citizen once they have returned home, or in extreme cases extraterritorially arrest and prosecute.<ref name=\"Circumvention Tourism\"/> In Ireland, especially, in the 1980s-90s there were cases of young rape victims who were banned from traveling to Europe to get legal abortions. Ultimately, Ireland\u2019s Supreme Court overturned the ban; they and many other countries have since created \"right to travel\" amendments.<ref name=\"Circumvention Tourism\"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Spreng|first1=Jennifer|title=Abortion and Divorce Law in Ireland|date=2004|publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc|location=Jefferson, NC|isbn=978-0786416752|page=150}}</ref>\n\n===Ethical issues===\nThere can be major ethical issues around medical tourism.<ref name=\"AHC\"/> For example, the illegal purchase of organs and tissues for transplantation had been methodically documented and studied in countries such as India,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://future.iftf.org/2006/04/the_dark_side_o.html |title=IFTF's Future Now: The dark side of medical tourism |publisher=Future.iftf.org |date=2006-04-19 |accessdate=2011-10-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929135242/http://future.iftf.org/2006/04/the_dark_side_o.html |archive-date=2011-09-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2008/02/09/MN23UPQ0K.DTL | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | title=Organ-transplant black market thrives in India | first=Anuj | last=Chopra | date=February 9, 2008}}</ref> China,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.epochtimes.com/news/7-5-23/55627.html |title= Transplants and Ethics in San Francisco |publisher=The Epoch Times |date=2007-05-23 |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref><ref name=orgharv>[[David Kilgour]], [[David Matas]] (6 July 2006, revised 31 January 2007)  [http://organharvestinvestigation.net An Independent Investigation into Allegations of Organ Harvesting of Falun Gong Practitioners in China] (free in 22 languages)  organharvestinvestigation.net</ref> Colombia<ref>{{cite journal | author = Lee Mendoza Roger | year = 2010 | title = Colombia's organ trade: Evidence from Bogot\u00e1 and Medell\u00edn | journal = Journal of Public Health | volume = 18 | issue = 4| pages = 375\u2013384 | doi=10.1007/s10389-010-0320-3}}</ref> and the Philippines.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Roger Lee Mendoza|date=2010|title=Price deflation and the underground organ economy in the Philippines|journal=Oxford Journal of Public Health|volume=33 |issue=1 |pages=101\u2013107|url=http://jpubhealth.oxfordjournals.org/content/33/1/101.abstract}}</ref>  The [[Declaration of Istanbul]] distinguishes between ethically problematic \"transplant tourism\" and \"travel for transplantation\".<ref>{{cite journal | author = Participants in the International Summit on Transplant Tourism and Organ Trafficking convened by The Transplantation Society and International Society of Nephrology in Istanbul, Turkey, 30 April to 2 May 2008 | year = 2008| title = The Declaration of Istanbul on Organ Trafficking and Transplant Tourism | doi = 10.1038/ki.2008.388 | pmid = 20142924| journal = Kidney International | volume = 74 | issue = 7| pages = 854\u201359 | pmc = 2813140 }}</ref>\n\nMedical tourism may raise broader ethical issues for the countries in which it is promoted. For example, in India, some argue that a \"policy of 'medical tourism for the classes and health missions for the masses' will lead to a deepening of the inequities\" already embedded in the health care system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.issuesinmedicalethics.org/132ed042.html|title=Indian Journal of Medical Ethics|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730071321/http://www.issuesinmedicalethics.org/132ed042.html|archive-date=30 July 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> In Thailand, in 2008 it was stated that, \"Doctors in Thailand have become so busy with foreigners that Thai patients are having trouble getting care\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=16735157 |title=Medical Tourism Creates Thai Doctor Shortage |publisher=NPR |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref> Medical tourism centered on new technologies, such as [[stem cell treatments]], is often criticized on grounds of fraud, blatant lack of scientific rationale and patient safety. However, when pioneering advanced technologies, such as providing 'unproven' therapies to patients outside of regular clinical trials, it is often challenging to differentiate between acceptable medical innovation and unacceptable patient exploitation.<ref>{{cite journal|title= Medical innovation versus stem cell tourism|date=2011-10-03 |pmid=19556497 | doi=10.1126/science.1171749 |volume=324 |issue=5935 |journal=Science |pages=1664\u20135 |vauthors=Lindvall O, Hyun I |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/66b5cc03376d042a04f66fee219c5d85b82ff8cf }}</ref><ref>[http://www.isscr.org/clinical_trans/index.cfm ISSCR Guidelines for the Clinical Translation of Stem Cells. 2008] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090603085208/http://www.isscr.org/clinical_trans/index.cfm |date=June 3, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n== Employer-sponsored health care in the US ==\nSome US employers have begun exploring medical travel programs as a way to cut employee [[health care prices in the United States|health care costs]].  Such proposals have raised stormy debates between employers and [[trade union]]s representing workers, with one union stating that it deplored the \"shocking new approach\" of offering employees overseas treatment in return for a share of the company's savings.  The unions also raise the issues of [[legal liability]] should something go wrong, and potential job losses in the US health care industry if treatment is [[outsourcing|outsourced]].<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/11/business/worldbusiness/11health.html Union Disrupts Plan to Send Ailing Workers to India for Cheaper Medical Care], [[The New York Times]]</ref>\n\nEmployers may offer incentives such as paying for air travel and waiving out-of-pocket expenses for care outside of the US. For example, in January 2008, Hannaford Bros., a supermarket chain based in Maine, began paying the entire medical bill for employees to travel to Singapore for hip and knee replacements, including travel for the patient and companion.<ref>McGinley, Laurie,\n[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB120283288380762505 \"Health Matters: The next wave of medical tourists might include you\"], Wall Street Journal, February 16, 2008. Retrieved March 13, 2008.</ref>  Medical travel packages can integrate with all types of [[health insurance]], including limited benefit plans,<ref>\n[http://www.bizjournals.com/houston/stories/2004/02/16/focus7.html \"Mini-Meds: Limited benefit plans provide cost-effective compromise\"] Houston Business Journal,</ref> [[preferred provider organization]]s and [[High Deductible Health Plan|high deductible health plan]]s.\n\nIn 2000, Blue Shield of California began the United States' first cross-border health plan. Patients in California could travel to one of the three certified hospitals in Mexico for treatment under California Blue Shield.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20101229023927/https://www.blueshieldca.com/bsc/newsroom/pr/United_Behavioral_Health.jhtml ]</ref> In 2007, a subsidiary of BlueCross BlueShield of South Carolina, Companion Global Healthcare, teamed up with hospitals in Thailand, Singapore, Turkey, Ireland, Costa Rica and India.<ref>Bruce Einhorn, [http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/08_12/b4076036777780.htm?chan=rss_topStories_ssi_5 \"Outsourcing the Patients\"], [[BusinessWeek]], March 13, 2008</ref> A 2008 article in ''[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]]'' discusses the globalization of healthcare and describes how various players in the US healthcare market have begun to explore it.<ref>Greg Lindsay,[http://www.fastcompany.com/magazine/125/medical-leave.html \"Medical Leave\"] Fast Company, May 2008. Retrieved October 15, 2008.</ref>\n\n== Destinations ==\n\n<!-- please leave this section as alphabetical -->\n\n===Africa and the Middle East===\n<!-- do not add a country subsection unless you can cite a reliable source.  Medical tourism blogs are not reliable sources. -->\n\n====South Africa====\n[[Healthcare in South Africa|South Africa]] is the first country in [[Africa]] to emerge as a medical tourism destination.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaclubsouthafrica.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1274:sa-medical-tourism-060809&catid=50:visitnews&Itemid=117 |title=: Medical tourism in SA |publisher=Mediaclubsouthafrica.com |date=2009-08-06 |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref>\n\n====Tunisia====\nOn the African scale, Tunisia ranks second in the field of health tourism. It is also named the world's second best thalassotherapy destination, behind France. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.webmanagercenter.com/2018/03/09/417123/tourisme-medical-la-tunisie-est-classee-au-2eme-rang-en-afrique/ |title=: Tourisme m\u00e9dical : La Tunisie est class\u00e9e au 2\u00e8me rang en Afrique |publisher=www.webmanagercenter.com |date=2018-03-09 |accessdate=2020-02-05}}</ref>\n\n====Jordan====\n[[Jordan]], through their Private Hospitals Association, attracted 250,000 international patients accompanied by more than 500,000 companions in 2012, with total revenues exceeding 1B US$.<ref name=\"JordanAward\">{{cite web|url=http://awards.imtj.com/results |title=IMTJ MEDICAL TRAVEL AWARDS 2014 |accessdate=2014-04-25}}</ref> Jordan won the Medical Destination of the year award in 2014 in the IMTJ Medical Travel Awards.<ref name=\"JordanAward\"/>\n\n====Israel====\n{{See also|Medical tourism in Israel}}\n[[Healthcare in Israel|Israel]] is a popular destination for medical tourism.<ref name=\"Haaretz\">[http://www.haaretz.com/news/national/health-ministry-to-probe-israel-medical-tourism-industry-following-haaretz-expose-1.325424 Health Ministry to probe Israel medical tourism industry following Haaretz expos\u00e9], [[Haaretz]], November 18, 2010</ref> Many medical tourists to Israel come from Europe, particularly the former Soviet Union, as well as the United States, Australia, Cyprus, and South Africa. Medical tourists come to Israel for a variety of surgical procedures and therapies, including bone marrow transplants, heart surgery, and catheterization, oncological and neurological treatments, orthopedic procedures, car accident rehabilitation, and [[in-vitro fertilization]]. Israel's popularity as a destination for medical tourism stems from its status as a developed country with a high-quality level of medical care, while at the same time having lower medical costs than many other developed countries. Israel is particularly popular as a destination for bone marrow transplants among Cypriots, as the procedure is not available in Cyprus, and for orthopedic procedures among Americans, as the cost of orthopedic procedures in Israel is about half that of in the United States. Israel is a particularly popular destination for people seeking IVF treatments. Medical tourists in Israel use both public and private hospitals, and all major Israeli hospitals offer medical tourism packages which typically cost far less than comparable procedures than in facilities elsewhere with a similarly high standard of care. In 2014, it was estimated that roughly 50,000 medical tourists came to Israel annually.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.imtj.com/articles/update-medical-tourism-development-israel/ | title=An overview of medical tourism in Israel &#124; IMTJ}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/israel-ranks-as-a-top-medical-tourism-destination/ | title=Israel ranks high as a medical tourism destination}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=http://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/culture/health/1.631674 | title=Doing Fertility Treatments in Israel: Pros and Cons| newspaper=Haaretz| date=2015-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.zendette.com/2015/04/14/medical-tourism-why-israel/ | title=Medical tourism \u2013 why Israel?| date=2015-04-14}}</ref> There are reports that these medical tourists obtain preferential treatment, to the detriment of local patients.<ref name=\"Haaretz\" /> In addition, some people come to Israel to visit health resorts at the [[Dead Sea]],<ref name=\"Haaretz\"/> and on [[Lake Kinneret]].\n\n====Iran====\nIn 2012, 30,000 people came to [[Healthcare in Iran|Iran]] to receive medical treatment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.farsnews.com/newstext.php?nn=9010171549 |title=Fars News Agency :: Ahmadinejad Stresses Iran's Growing Medical Tourism Industry |publisher=English.farsnews.com |date=2012-01-17 |accessdate=2012-02-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://swap.stanford.edu/20120213085015/http%3A//english.farsnews.com/newstext.php?nn%3D9010171549 |archivedate=2012-02-13 }}</ref>\nIn 2015, it is estimated that between 150,000 and 200,000 health tourists came to Iran, and this figure is expected to rise to 500,000 a year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irna.ir/en/News/81456929/ |title=500,000 health tourists coming to Iran for medical treatment |website=Irna.ir |date= |accessdate=2017-01-08}}</ref>\n\n====United Arab Emirates====\nUnited Arab Emirates, especially Dubai, Abu Dhabi, Ras Al Khaimah is a popular destination for medical tourism. The Dubai Health authority has been spearheading medical tourism into UAE, especially Dubai. However, hospitals providing medical tourism are spread all over the seven emirates. UAE has the distinction of having the maximum number of JCI accredited hospitals (under various heads).<ref>https://www.jointcommissioninternational.org/about-jci/jci-accredited-organizations/?c=United%20Arab%20Emirates</ref> UAE has inbound medical tourism as well as people going out for medical treatment. The inbound tourism usually is from African countries like Nigeria, Kenya, Uganda, Rwanda, etc. The outbound can be categorised into two segments - the local population (citizens of UAE) and the expats. The locals prefer to go to European destinations like the U.K., Germany etc. The expats prefer to go back to their home countries for treatment.\n\n===Americas===\n<!-- do not add a country subsection unless you can cite a reliable source.  Medical tourism blogs are not reliable sources. -->\n\n====Brazil====\nIn [[Healthcare in Brazil|Brazil]], [[Albert Einstein Hospital]] in S\u00e3o Paulo was the first JCI-accredited facility outside of the US,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/hospital-israelita-albert-einstein-becomes-first-hospital-accredited-by-joint-commission-international-72671117.html |title=Hospital Israelita Albert Einstein Becomes First Hospital Accredited by Joint Commission International |accessdate=2014-11-12 |format=Blog |publisher=PR Newswire}}</ref> and more than a dozen Brazilian medical facilities have since been similarly accredited.<ref name=\"JCI\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jointcommissioninternational.org/JCI-Accredited-Organizations/ |title=(JCI) Accredited Organizations |publisher=Joint Commission International |accessdate=2011-10-29 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/69sdmHwPX?url=http://www.jointcommissioninternational.org/JCI-Accredited-Organizations/ |archive-date=2012-08-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n====Mexico====\n\nMexico has 98 hospitals accredited by the country\u2019s Federal Health Ministry and seven hospitals which are JCI-accredited. Mexico is most reputed for advanced care in dentistry and cosmetic surgery. Medical care in Mexico saves a patient 40% to 65% compared to the cost of similar services in the US.\n\n====Canada====\nIn comparison to US health costs, patients can save 30 to 60 percent on health costs in [[Healthcare in Canada|Canada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.deloitte.com/content/dam/Deloitte/ca/Documents/life-sciences-health-care/ca-en-health-care-life-sciences-evolving-medical-tourism-exploring-a-new-frontier.pdf |title=Evolving medical tourism in Canada |website=Deloitte.com |accessdate=2017-01-08}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1990s, Americans illegally using counterfeit, borrowed, or fraudulently obtained Canadian health insurance cards to obtain free healthcare in Canada became a serious issue due to the high costs it imposed.<ref>{{cite news|last=Farnsworth |first=Clyde H. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/12/20/world/americans-filching-free-health-care-in-canada.html?pagewanted=all |title=Americans Filching Free Health Care in Canada |location=Ontario (Canada); Canada; United States |website=NYTimes.com |date=1993-12-20 |accessdate=2017-01-08}}</ref>\n\n====Costa Rica====\nIn Costa Rica, there are two [[Joint Commission on Accreditation of Healthcare Organizations#International accreditation|Joint Commission International]] accredited (JCI) hospitals. Both are in San Jose, Costa Rica. When the World Health Organization (WHO) ranked the world's health systems in the year 2000, Costa Rica was ranked as no. 26, which was higher than the US, and together with Dominica it dominated the list amongst the Central American countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imtj.com/news/?entryid82=290909&source=email&campaign=imtj_news_110527 |title=South Korea wants to expand medical tourism beyond cosmetic surgery |publisher=Imtj.com |date=2009-05-08 |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref>\n\nThe Deloitte Center for Health Solutions in 2008 reported a cost savings average of between 30-70 percent of US prices.<ref>[http://www.deloitte.com/assets/Dcom-Croatia/Local%20Assets/Documents/hr_Medical_tourism(3).pdf Medical Tourism Consumers in Search of Value] 2008 Deloitte Development LLC</ref> In 2019 a knee operation in [[Clinica Biblica]]  which would have cost around $44,000 in the USA cost $12,200.<ref>{{cite news |title=I had my misgivings about going abroad for surgery |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-47704954 |accessdate=7 April 2019 |publisher=BBC |date=28 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Cayman Islands====\n{{main|Health City Cayman Islands}}\n\n====Cuba====\n{{main|Health care in Cuba#Health tourism and pharmaceutics}}\n\n====United States====\n{{Main|Health care in the United States}}\nA report of [[McKinsey and Co.]] from 2008 found that between 60,000 and 85,000 medical tourists were traveling worldwide for the purpose of receiving in-patient medical care.<ref name=Forbes08>{{cite news |author=Allison Van Dusen |title=U.S. Hospitals Worth The Trip |url=https://www.forbes.com/2008/05/25/health-hospitals-care-forbeslife-cx_avd_outsourcing08_0529healthoutsourcing.html |quote=It narrowly defined medical travelers as only those whose primary and explicit purpose in traveling was to obtain in-patient medical treatment in a foreign country, putting the total number of travelers at 60,000 to 85,000 per year. |newspaper=[[Forbes]] |date=May 29, 2008 |accessdate=2012-09-17 }}</ref> Some have estimated that 750,000 American medical tourists traveled from the United States to other countries in 2007 (up from 500,000 in 2006).<ref name=Hansen08>Fred Hansen, [http://web.mnstate.edu/robertsb/390/A%20revolution%20in%20healthcare%20Medicine%20meets%20the%20marketplace.pdf], [[Institute of Public Affairs]] review article (January 2008).</ref> According to the McKinsey and Co Report [http://www.heal-wheel-india.com/white-pappers/McKinsey-Report-Medical-Travel.pdf (report)], 45% of North American medical tourists travel to Asia, 26% go to Latin America, 2% go to the Middle East, and 27% travel to another country in North America. None travel to Europe. \n\nThe availability of advanced medical technology and sophisticated training of physicians are cited as driving motivators for growth in foreigners traveling to the US for medical care,<ref name=Forbes08/> whereas the low costs for hospital stays and major/complex procedures at Western-accredited medical facilities abroad are cited as major motivators for American travelers.<ref name=Hansen08/> Also, the decline in [[U.S. currency#International use|value of the US dollar]] between 2007 and 2013 used to offer additional incentives for foreign travel to the US, although cost differences between the US and many locations in Asia are larger than any currency fluctuations.\n\nSeveral major medical centers and teaching hospitals offer international patient centers that cater to patients from foreign countries who seek medical treatment in the US.<ref>[http://stanfordhospital.org/forPatients/patientServices/internationalMedicalServices.html International Medical Services] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612212550/http://stanfordhospital.org/forPatients/patientServices/internationalMedicalServices.html |date=2010-06-12 }}, [[Stanford Hospital|Stanford Hospital & Clinics]]</ref> Many of these organizations offer service coordinators to assist international patients with arrangements for medical care, accommodations, finances and transportation including [[air ambulance]] services.\n\n===Asia and the Pacific Islands===\n<!-- do not add a country subsection unless you can cite a reliable source.  Medical tourism blogs are not reliable sources. -->\n\n====China====\n{{Main|Healthcare in China}}\n[[Ctrip]]'s 2016 Online Medical Tourism Report indicates that the number of travelers who enroll in the oversea medical tourism through its platform increased fivefold over the previous year, and more than 500,000 Chinese visitors are expected to go on medical tourism. The top ten medical tourism destinations are Japan, Korea, the US, Taiwan, Germany, Singapore, Malaysia, Sweden, Thailand, and India.<ref name=\"marce\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.marcetable.com/2017/01/29/medical-tourism-2016-report-china/|title=2016 China Medical Tourism Report|date=2017-01-29|website=Marcetable|access-date=2017-02-12}}</ref>  Regular health checks made up the majority share of Chinese medical tourism in 2016, representing over 50% of all medical tourism trips for tourists originating in China.<ref name=\"marce\"/>\n\n====Hong Kong====\nAll twelve of Hong Kong's private hospitals have been surveyed and accredited by the UK's Trent Accreditation Scheme since early 2001.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080227022521/http://www.1stor.co.uk/trentaccreditationscheme.org/news/tasnews6-200110.pdf]</ref>\n\n====India====\n{{Main|Medical tourism in India}}\nMedical tourism is a growing sector in [[Healthcare in India|India]]. India is becoming the 2nd medical tourism destination after Thailand. [[Chennai]] is regarded as \"India's Health City\" as it attracts 45% of health tourists visiting India and 40% of domestic health tourists.\n\nIndia\u2019s medical tourism sector was expected to experience an annual growth rate of 30% from 2012, making it a $2 billion industry by 2015.<ref>[http://www.indianhealthcare.in/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&catid=39%3ANews&id=357%3AINDIAN+MEDICAL+TOURISM+TO+TOUCH+RS+9,500+CRORE+BY+2015:+ASSOCHAM&sectionid=17&Itemid=77 Indian Medical Tourism To Touch Rs 9,500 Crore By 2015], The Economic Times, posted on IndianHealthCare.in</ref><ref name=\"MedicalCapitalsPlaceInHistory\">{{cite news\n | last = Hamid\n | first = Zubeda\n | title = The medical capital's place in history\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n | pages =\n | language =\n | date = 20 August 2012\n | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/article3796305.ece\n | accessdate = 15 Sep 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, the [[Government of India|Indian government]] made it easier for foreigners to receive medical treatment without necessarily applying for a medical visa. These initiatives by Indian government will help Medical Tourism market to reach around $9 Billion in 2020. Furthermore the major reason for foreign tourist to choose India is because, It boasts 38 [[List of hospitals in India|hospitals]] accredited by the [[Joint Commission|Joint Commission International]].\n<ref name=\"India\u2019s Medical Tourism Market Could Reach $9 Billion Next Year Buoyed By Low Cost, High Quality Service\">{{cite news\n | last = Palash\n | first = Ghosh\n | title = India's Medical Tourism Market\n | newspaper = International business times\n | pages = Business\n | language = English\n | date = 26 November 2019\n | url = https://www.ibtimes.com/indias-medical-tourism-market-could-reach-9-billion-next-year-buoyed-low-cost-high-2874034\n | accessdate = 9 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs medical treatment costs in the developed world balloon\u2014with the United States leading the way\u2014more and more Westerners are finding the prospect of international travel for medical care increasingly appealing.  An estimated 150,000 of these travel to India for low-priced healthcare procedures every year. \n\nIndia is increasingly becoming popular with Africans seeking medical treatment overseas, because of it boast highly qualified doctors and [[State of the art|state-of-the-art equipment]], and the treatments are approved by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) and the [[Food and Drug Administration|US Food and Drug Administration]].\n<ref name=\"India\u2019s medical tourism gets Africans\u2019 attention\">\n{{cite news|url=https://www.un.org/africarenewal/magazine/december-2016-march-2017/india%E2%80%99s-medical-tourism-gets-africans%E2%80%99-attention|title=India's medical tourism|last=Pavithra|first=rao|date=26 March 2017|newspaper=Africa Renewal|accessdate=10 December 2019|pages=Health & Well being|language=English}}</ref> Many patients from [[Africa]] prefer Apollo & Medobal [[Healthcare in India|healthcare]], which are headquartered in [[Chennai]] in India\u2019s state of Tamil Nadu. [[Cosmetic surgery]], [[bariatric surgery]], [[Knee Cap|knee cap replacements]], [[Liver transplantation|liver transplants]], and [[Management of cancer|cancer treatments]] are some of the most sought out medical tourism procedures chosen by foreigners.\n\n====Malaysia====\n{{Main|Medical tourism in Malaysia}}The majority of the foreign patients seeking medical treatments in Malaysia are from Indonesia, with smaller numbers of foreign patients coming from India, Singapore, Japan, Australia, Europe, the USA and the Middle East. In 2008, Indonesians comprised 75% of all foreign patients receiving care in Malaysia; Europeans, 3%; Japanese, 3%; Singaporeans, 1% and citizens from Middle Eastern countries, 1%. By 2011, Indonesians comprised 57% of all foreign patients in Malaysia as the number of patients of other nationalities grew.\n\nHealth insurance companies in Singapore have recently permitted their policyholders to be treated in Malaysia where services are cheaper than in Singapore.\n\n====New Zealand====\n{{Main|Health care in New Zealand}}\nIn 2008, it was estimated that on average New Zealand's surgical costs are around 15 to 20% the cost of the same surgical procedure in the USA.<ref name=\"Eleanor Black Watkin\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/07/03/AR2008070303532_pf.html|title=One Company With an Eye on U.S. Customers|last=Eleanor Black Watkin|date=July 8, 2008|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=1 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Pakistan====\n{{Main|Medical tourism in Pakistan}}\n\n====Singapore====\n[[Healthcare in Singapore|Singapore]] has a dozen hospitals and health centers with JCI accreditation.<ref>[http://www.jointcommissioninternational.org/about-jci/jci-accredited-organizations/?c=SG Joint Commission International (JCI) Accredited Organizations]</ref>  In 2013 medical expenditure generated from medical tourists, mostly from more complex medical procedures, such as heart surgery, was S$832 million, a decline of 25 percent from 2012's S$1.11 billion, as the hospitals faced more competition from neighbouring countries for less complex work.<ref>{{cite news|title=The rise of 5-star hospitals in Singapore|url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/hotel-or-hospital|accessdate=10 February 2017|publisher=Today on line|date=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Thailand====\n{{Main|Health in Thailand|Tourism in Thailand}}\nForeigners seeking treatment for everything from open-heart surgery to fertility treatments have made [[Thailand]] and its accredited hospitals a popular destination for medical tourism, attracting an estimated 2.81 million patients in 2015, up 10.2 percent.<ref>{{cite news|title=Medical Tourism in Thailand: When Treatment Costs and Starbucks Clash|url=http://www.medicaltourismmag.com/medical-tourism-in-thailand-when-treatment-costs-and-starbucks-clash/|accessdate=14 October 2015|work=Medical Tourism Magazine|date=2015-10-13}}</ref> In 2013, medical tourists spent as much as US$4.7 billion, according to government statistics.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mellor|first1=William|title=Medical Tourists Flock to Thailand Spurring Post-Coup Economy|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-11-18/medical-tourists-flock-to-thailand-spurring-post-coup-economy|accessdate=19 February 2015|work=Bloomberg|date=19 November 2014}}</ref> {{asof|2019}}, with 64 accredited hospitals, Thailand is currently among the top 10 medical tourism destinations in the world. In 2017, Thailand registered 3.3 million visits by foreigners seeking specialised medical treatment. In 2018, this number grew to 3.5 million.<ref name=\"DM-20190212\">{{cite news |last1=Otage |first1=Stephen |title=Uganda: What Uganda Can Learn From Thailand's Medical Tourism |url=https://www.monitor.co.ug/Business/Prosper/What-Uganda-can-learn-Thailand-medical-tourism/688616-4977826-11vacmh/index.html |accessdate=15 February 2019 |work=Daily Monitor |date=12 February 2019 |location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\n===Europe===\n\nIn 2006, it was ruled that under the conditions of the E112 European health scheme, UK health authorities had to pay the bill if one of their patients could establish urgent medical reasons for seeking quicker treatment in another European union country.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thompsons.law.co.uk/clinical-negligence/nhs-waiting-lists-targets.htm |title=NHS Waiting lists: targets and England&Wales comparison |publisher=Thompsons.law.co.uk |date=2006-05-16 |accessdate=2011-10-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202222100/http://www.thompsons.law.co.uk/clinical-negligence/nhs-waiting-lists-targets.htm |archive-date=2014-02-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe European directive on the application of patients\u2019 rights to cross-border healthcare was agreed in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|title=Outcomes in EHCI 2015|url=http://www.healthpowerhouse.com/files/EHCI_2015/EHCI_2015_report.pdf|accessdate=27 January 2016|publisher=Health Consumer Powerhouse|date=26 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606082345/http://www.healthpowerhouse.com/files/EHCI_2015/EHCI_2015_report.pdf|archive-date=6 June 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAn online survey of EU migrants, mostly from Poland, Hungary and Romania, in the UK by the Centre for Population Change in 2019 showed that 46% of them preferred the health system in their country of origin. Only 36% preferred NHS medical treatment, and fewer among those from Western Europe.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Worstall |first1=Tim |title=NHS Not Much Cop Say Those Who've Tried Other Health Care Systems |url=https://www.continentaltelegraph.com/healthcare/nhs-not-much-cop-say-those-whove-tried-other-health-care-systems/ |accessdate=25 March 2019 |publisher=Continental Telegraph |date=22 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Azerbaijan====\nAzerbaijan is a target of health tourists from Iran, Turkey, Georgia and Russia. The Bona Dea International Hospital in Baku was built in 2018 to attract international custom, and has staff from various European countries.<ref>{{cite news |title=Azerbaijan Improves Medical Infrastructure To Lure Health-Conscious Travelers |url=https://caspiannews.com/news-detail/azerbaijan-improves-medical-infrastructure-to-lure-health-conscious-travelers-2018-4-13-15/ |accessdate=7 March 2019 |publisher=Caspian News |date=16 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Croatia====\nCroatia has some claims to be the oldest health tourism destination in Europe, as the [[Hygienic Association of Hvar]] was founded in 1868.<ref>{{cite news |title=History of Tourism from 1868 |url=https://www.total-croatia-news.com/history-2/3218-history-of-tourism-from-1868 |accessdate=27 December 2018 |publisher=Total Croatia |date=24 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Finland====\nOn December 9, 2013, the City of Helsinki decided that all minors under the age of 18 and all pregnant mothers living in Helsinki without a valid visa or residence permit are [[Healthcare in Finland|granted the right to the same health care]] and at the same price as all citizens of the city. This service will be available sometime early year 2014. Volunteer doctors of Global Clinic have tried to help these people, for whom only acute care has been available. This means that the [[Healthcare in Finland|Finnish health care system]] is open for all people coming outside of the European Union. The service covers special child health care, maternity clinics and specialist medical care etc. practically for free. It is still unclear if this will increase so called health care tourism, because all you have to do is come to Helsinki as a tourist and let the visa expire.\n\nThe Global Clinic in Turku offers health care for all undocumented immigrants for free.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://yle.fi/uutiset/turku_clinic_offers_health_care_for_undocumented_immigrants/6592725 |title=Turku clinic offers health care for undocumented immigrants |accessdate=2015-01-22}}</ref>\n\n====France====\nBritish NHS patients have been offered treatment in [[Health care in France|France]] to reduce waiting lists for hip, knee and cataract surgery since 2002.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/1770348.stm | work=BBC News | title=NHS patients recover after surgery abroad | date=January 19, 2002}}</ref> France is a popular tourist destination but also ranked the world's leading health care system by the [[World Health Organization]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/whr/2000/media_centre/press_release/en/|title=World Health Organization Assesses the World's Health Systems|publisher=|accessdate=13 October 2016}}</ref>  [[European Court of Justice]] said that [[National Health Service (England)]] has to pay back British patients.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/4985190.stm|title=BBC NEWS - Health - NHS told to fund treatment abroad|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe number of patients is growing, and in 2016, France scored # 7 in the Medical Tourism Index.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medicaltourismindex.com/overview/destination-ranking/|title=Medical Tourism Index: Destination Ranking|publisher=|accessdate=13 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Germany====\nIn 2017 there were said to be around 250,000 foreign patients who brought more than 1.2 billion euros income to German hospitals. Some were visitors who fell ill unexpectedly, but it is estimated that more than 40 percent came for planned treatment, the majority from Poland, the Netherlands or France.  There have long been medical tourists from the Middle East. University hospitals and the large municipal clinics, such as [[University Hospital Freiburg]] or [[Vivantes]] in Berlin, are the most popular destinations.<ref>{{cite news |title=Das Riesengesch\u00e4ft mit dem Medizintourismus in Deutschland |url=https://www.dw.com/de/das-riesengesch%C3%A4ft-mit-dem-medizintourismus-in-deutschland/a-42114866 |accessdate=7 March 2019 |publisher=DW |date=11 January 2018}}</ref>  Some require payment in full before they start treatment.<ref>{{cite web |title=Information on Treatment Costs |url=https://www.heidelberg-university-hospital.com/en/finance/ |website=Heildelberg University |accessdate=20 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Hallwang Clinic GmbH]] is said to be the most high profile clinic in the European private cancer industry, centred in Germany, which attracts patients from the US, the UK,  Australia and the Middle East,<ref>{{cite news |title=Cancer crowdfunding 'couldn't save my daughter' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-47442946 |accessdate=6 March 2019 |publisher=BBC |date=6 March 2019}}</ref> offering a variety of different treatments, some of which do not appear to be evidence based; the clinic has been accused of selling false hope.<ref>{{cite news |title=The deadly false hope of German alternative cancer clinics |url=https://sciencebasedmedicine.org/the-deadly-false-hope-of-german-cancer-clinics/ |accessdate=7 March 2019 |publisher=sciencebasedmedicine.org |date=26 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Lithuania====\nHealth Tourism Lithuania, a booking agent, was established in 2018, focusing on the Scandinavian market, but in 2019 in response to longer waiting lists in the [[NHS]] noticed an increase in enquiries about hip replacements, in addition to the existing interest in cosmetic surgery and dentistry from Britons. A hip replacement costs \u00a33,340, about a third of the price of a commercial procedure in the UK.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lithuania to offer Britons cheap surgery as millions stuck on longest NHS waiting list |url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/1132690/NHS-crisis-lithuania-hospitals-Reda-Ambrozaite-HTL-Peter-Gaillard-hip-replacement |accessdate=1 June 2019 |publisher=Express |date=27 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Serbia====\n[[Healthcare in Serbia|Serbia]] has a variety of clinics catering to medical tourists in areas of cosmetic surgery, dental care, fertility treatment and weight loss procedures.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.treatmentabroad.com/destinations/serbia/why-choose-serbia |title=Why choose Serbia for medical tourism |website=Treatmentabroad.com |date=2013-10-08 |accessdate=2017-01-08}}</ref> The country is also a major international hub for gender reassignment surgery.<ref>{{cite news|author=Dan Bilefsky |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/24/world/europe/serbia-becomes-a-hub-for-sex-change-surgery.html |title=Serbia Becomes a Hub for Sex-Change Surgery |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=2012-07-23 |accessdate=2017-01-08}}</ref>\n\n====Russia====\nIn his address to the Federal Assembly of the Russian Federation dated March 1, 2018, Russian President Vladimir Putin stressed the need to develop health care and export services in the field of medicine and tourism.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u041f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u0421\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044e |url=http://www.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/56957 |website=kremlin.ru |accessdate=16 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn accordance with the decree of the President of the Russian Federation of May 7, 2018 \u2116 204 \"on national goals and strategic objectives of the development of the Russian Federation for the period up to 2024\" the volume of exports of medical services by 2024 will have to be $1 billion per year. RAMT in order to implement the Decree of the President of the Russian Federation of 7 May 2018 \u2116 204, the Federal non-profit organization [[Russian Association of Medical Tourism]] was established.\n\n====Turkey====\nThe cost of medical recourses in [[Health care in Turkey|Turkey]] is quite affordable compared to Western European countries. Therefore, thousands of people each year travel to Turkey for their medical treatments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.turkishhealthcaretravelcouncil.org/|title=THTC - Turkish Healthcare Travel Council|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref> Turkey is especially becoming a hub for hair transplant surgery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/bw/articles/2013-05-10/turkeys-thriving-business-in-hair-beard-and-mustache-implants|title=Turkey's Thriving Business in Hair, Beard, and Mustache Implants|author=Sarah A. Topol|work=Businessweek.com|accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref> Almost 178 thousand tourists visited for health purposes in the first six months of 2018.  67% used private hospital, 24% public hospitals and 9% university hospitals.  The Regulation on International Health Tourism and Tourist Health came into force on 13 July 2017. It only applies to those coming specifically for treatment.<ref>{{cite news |title=International Health Tourism in Turkey |url=https://www.lexology.com/library/detail.aspx?g=640bb91d-e7b6-4ef4-bf87-2fd5abf8f69b& |accessdate=13 February 2019 |publisher=Lexology |date=8 January 2018}}</ref> \n\n====United Kingdom====\n\nThe [[National Health Service]] is publicly owned. It attracts medical tourism principally to specialist centres in London. Some private hospitals and clinics in the United Kingdom are medical tourism destinations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imtj.com/articles/2009/the-forgotten-medical-tourism-destination-30026/?locale=en|title=The forgotten medical tourism destination|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2015|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130126192002/http://www.imtj.com/articles/2009/the-forgotten-medical-tourism-destination-30026/?locale=en|archive-date=26 January 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.imtj.com/news/?EntryId82=285641 |title=UK: New London agency could promote medical tourism |date=20 April 2011}}</ref> UK private hospitals have mandatory registration with the UK's watchdog, the [[Care Quality Commission]]).\n\nThe vast majority of medical tourism in the UK is attracted to London where there are 25 private hospitals and clinics and 12 private patient units run by NHS hospital trusts. American organisations including the [[Cleveland Clinic]], the [[Mayo Clinic]] and [[Ambulatory Surgery International]] have established operations in London.   In 2017 there was a 3% decline in the \u00a31.55 billion market because of fewer clients from the Middle East, who perceive London as expensive. Overseas patients coming to London are now more likely to be looking for cancer treatment than orthopaedics. Income for NHS providers rose by 9% in 2018-9, pushing the [[Royal Marsden]] nearer the 50% statutory limit.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cancer care becomes biggest earner for London's private hospitals |url=https://www.ft.com/content/befcda6c-2b91-11e9-a5ab-ff8ef2b976c7 |accessdate=19 March 2019 |publisher=Financial Times |date=8 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n=====Abuse=====\nIt is alleged that health tourists in the UK often target the NHS for its free-at-the-point-of-care treatment, allegedly costing the NHS up to \u00a3200 million.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://fullfact.org/health/costs_health_tourism-37227|title= Health tourists: How much do they cost and who pays? - Full Fact|date=6 September 2015}}</ref>  A study in 2013 concluded that the UK was a net exporter of medical tourists, with 63,000 UK residents travelling abroad for treatment and about 52,000 patients getting treatment in UK.  Medical tourists treated as private patients by NHS trusts are more profitable than UK private patients, yielding close to a quarter of the revenue from only seven percent of volume of cases.  UK dental patients largely go to Hungary and Poland. Fertility tourists mostly travel to Eastern Europe, Cyprus and Spain.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hannefeld|first1=Johanna|last2=Horsfall|first2=Daniel|last3=Lunt|first3=Neil|last4=Smith|first4=Richard|title=Medical Tourism: A Cost or Benefit to the NHS?|journal=PLOS ONE|date=24 October 2013|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0070406|pmid=24204556|pmc=3812100|volume=8|issue=10|pages=e70406|bibcode=2013PLoSO...870406H}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2015 immigration officers from the [[Border Force]] were stationed in [[St George's University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust]] to train staff to identify \"potentially chargeable patients\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Immigration officers at London trust for patient charging pilot|url=http://www.lgcplus.com/news/health/social-care/immigration-officers-at-london-trust-for-patient-charging-pilot/5087970.article|accessdate=24 September 2015|publisher=Local Government Chronicle|date=20 July 2015}}</ref>  In October 2016 the trust announced that it planned to require photo identity papers or proof of their right to remain in the UK such as asylum status or a visa for pregnant women. Those not able to provide satisfactory documents would be sent to the trust's overseas patient team \"for specialist document screening, in liaison with the [[UK Border Agency]] and the Home Office.\u201d  It was estimated that \u00a34.6 million a year was spent on care for ineligible patients.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pregnant women could need photo ID to get maternity care as St George's Hospital in Tooting cracks down on NHS tourism|url=http://www.richmondandtwickenhamtimes.co.uk/news/14794980.Pregnant_women_could_need_photo_ID_to_get_maternity_care_at_hospital/|accessdate=29 October 2016|publisher=Richmond and Twickenham Times|date=11 October 2016}}</ref> A pilot scheme to check whether patients were entitled to free NHS care in 18 [[NHS trusts]],  11 in London, for two months in 2017 asked 8,894 people for two forms of ID prior to non-emergency care. Only 50 were not eligible for free NHS treatment. Campaigners claimed this was \u201cpart of the Government\u2019s hostile environment policy\u201d, and that in [[Newham University Hospital|Newham hospital]] \"you will see huge signs saying you may not be eligible for free NHS treatment\".<ref>{{cite news|title=8,900 checks on NHS 'health tourists' find just 50 liable to pay|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/health/8900-checks-on-nhs-health-tourists-find-just-50-liable-to-pay-a3850121.html|accessdate=30 May 2018|publisher=Evening Standard|date=29 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe bills issued to patients thought to be ineligible far exceed the sums actually collected.  Most trusts do not have dedicated staff for the task. Ineligible patients generally live overseas, many have no money, and some demonstrate that they were eligible for free treatment after invoices have been issued. <ref>{{cite news |title=Trusts missing out on tens of millions from overseas patients |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/finance-and-efficiency/trusts-missing-out-on-tens-of-millions-from-overseas-patients/7026384.article |accessdate=9 January 2020 |publisher=Health Service Journal |date=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nSee also [[Immigration health surcharge]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Medicine}}\n* [[Wellness tourism]]\n*[[Consumer import of prescription drugs]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikivoyage|Medical tourism}}<!-- PLEASE do not add commercial links, or links to medical tourism companies here -->\n\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/11/02/AR2006110200728_pf.html Businesses May Move Health Care Overseas (Washington Post)]\n* [http://www.cbc.ca/news2/background/healthcare/medicaltourism.html CBC News on \"Medical tourism: Need surgery, will travel\"]\n* [http://abcnews.go.com/Business/IndustryInfo/story?id=2320839&page=1 A Cut Below: Americans Look Abroad for Health Care (ABC News)]\n* [http://www.cbsnews.com/video/watch/?id=781417n|Thailand's Medical Tourism, 60 Minutes (CBS News)]\n\n{{Tourism}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Medical Tourism}}\n[[Category:Medical tourism| ]]\n", "text_old": "'''Medical tourism''' refers to people traveling abroad to obtain medical treatment. In the past, this usually referred to those who traveled from less-developed countries to major medical centers in highly developed countries for treatment unavailable at home.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Horowitz|first1=Michael D.|last2=Rosensweig|first2=Jeffrey A.|last3=Jones|first3=Christopher A.|year=2007|title=Medical Tourism: Globalization of the Healthcare Marketplace|journal=MedGenMed|volume=9|issue=4|page=33|pmc=2234298|pmid=18311383}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://web.nchu.edu.tw/pweb/users/hychuo/lesson/5877.pdf|title=Medical tourism--health care in the global economy|publisher=Physician Exec|accessdate=16 September 2012}}</ref> However, in recent years it may equally refer to those from developed countries who travel to developing countries for lower-priced medical treatments. The motivation may be also for medical services unavailable or non-licensed in the home country: There are differences between the medical agencies (FDA, EMA etc.) world-wide, whether a drug is approved in their country or not. Even within Europe, although therapy protocols might be approved by the European Medical Agency (EMA), several countries have their own review organizations (i.e. NICE by the NHS) in order to evaluate whether the same therapy protocol would be \"cost-effective\", so that patients face differences in the therapy protocols, particularly in the access of these drugs, which might be partially explained by the financial strength of the particular Health System.\n\nMedical tourism most often is for [[surgery|surgeries]] (cosmetic or otherwise) or similar treatments, though people also travel for [[dental tourism]] or [[fertility tourism]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wordspy.com/words/fertilitytourism.asp|title=fertility tourism|author=Paul McFedries|date=2006-05-17|publisher=Word Spy|accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref> People with rare conditions may travel to countries where the treatment is better understood. However, almost all types of health care are available, including [[psychiatry]], alternative medicine, convalescent care, and even burial services.\n\nHealth tourism is a wider term for travel that focuses on medical treatments and the use of healthcare services. It covers a wide field of health-oriented, tourism ranging from preventive and health-conductive treatment to rehabilitational and curative forms of travel. [[Wellness tourism]] is a related field.\n\n==History==\nThe first recorded instance of people travelling for medical treatment dates back thousands of years to when [[Greeks|Greek]] pilgrims traveled from the eastern [[Mediterranean]] to a small area in the [[Saronic Gulf]] called [[Epidauria]].<ref>{{cite web|title=History of Medical Tourism|url=http://www.discovermedicaltourism.com/history/|website=Discovermedicaltourism.com|publisher=Discovermedicaltourism.com|accessdate=2015-11-03}}</ref> This territory was the sanctuary of the healing god [[Asklepios]].\n\n[[Spa town]]s and [[sanatorium|sanitaria]] were early forms of medical tourism. In 18th-century Europe patients visited spas because they were places with supposedly health-giving [[mineral water]]s, treating diseases from [[gout]] to [[liver]] disorders and [[bronchitis]].<ref name=\"Gahlinger2008\">Gahlinger, PM. The Medical Tourism Travel Guide: Your Complete Reference to Top-Quality, Low-Cost Dental, Cosmetic, Medical Care & Surgery Overseas. Sunrise River Press, 2008</ref>\n\n==Description==\nFactors that have led to the increasing popularity of medical travel include the high cost of health care, long wait times for certain procedures, the ease and affordability of international travel, and improvements in both technology and standards of care in many countries.<ref name=\"Goering March 28, 2008\">Laurie Goering, [http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chi-medical-tourism_goeringmar28,0,4555735.story  \"For big surgery, Delhi is dealing,\"] The ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', March 28, 2008  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080401041824/http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chi-medical-tourism_goeringmar28%2C0%2C4555735.story |date=April 1, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Tompkins|first1=Olga|title=Medical Tourism|journal=AAOHN Journal|date=2010|volume=58|issue=1|page=40|doi=10.3928/08910162-20091223-04|pmid=20102121}}</ref>  The avoidance of waiting times is the leading factor for medical tourism from the UK, whereas in the US, the main reason is cheaper prices abroad. Furthermore, death rates even in the developed countries differ extremely, i.e. UK versus seven other leading countries, including the US.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2013/sep/12/hospital-death-rates-england-higher-us|title=Hospital death rates in England 45% higher than in US, report finds|last=Ramesh|first=Randeep|date=2013-09-12|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-03-17|last2=editor|first2=social affairs|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nMany surgical procedures performed in medical tourism destinations cost a fraction of the price they do in other countries. For example, in the United States, a liver transplant that may cost $300,000 USD, would generally cost about $91,000 USD in Taiwan.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2004023,00.html | work=Time | first=Sarah | last=Tung | title=Is Taiwan Asia's Next One-Stop Plastic-Surgery Shop? | date=July 16, 2010}}</ref> A large draw to medical travel is convenience and speed. Countries that operate public health-care systems often have long wait times for certain operations, for example, an estimated 782,936 Canadian patients spent an average waiting time of 9.4 weeks on medical waiting lists in 2005.<ref>[http://www.fraserinstitute.org/Commerce.Web/product_files/PrivateCostofPublicQueues2005.pdf The Private Cost of Public Queues in 2005]{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, [[Fraser Institute]]</ref> Canada has also set waiting time benchmarks for non-urgent medical procedures, including a 26-week waiting period for a hip replacement and a 16-week wait for cataract surgery.<ref>[http://www.canada.com/Wait+times+shorter+some+medical+procedures+report/1528971/story.html Wait times shorter for some medical procedures: report.], [[Canwest News Service]]</ref>\n\nIn First World countries such as the United States, medical tourism has large growth prospects and potentially destabilizing implications.  A forecast by [[Deloitte Consulting]] published in August 2008 projected that medical tourism originating in the US could jump by a factor of ten over the next decade.  An estimated 750,000 Americans went abroad for health care in 2007, and the report estimated that 1.5 million would seek health care outside the US in 2008.  The growth in medical tourism has the potential to cost US health care providers billions of dollars in lost revenue.<ref>Linda A. Johnson, [http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2008/08/03/BUGA121GPF.DTL&type=health \"Americans look abroad to save on health care: Medical tourism could jump tenfold in next decade,\"] The [[San Francisco Chronicle]], August 3, 2008</ref>\n\nAn authority at the [[Harvard Business School]] stated that \"medical tourism is promoted much more heavily in the United Kingdom than in the United States\".<ref>Lagace, Martha [http://hbswk.hbs.edu/item/5814.html \"The Rise of Medical Tourism\"], Harvard Business School Working Knowledge, December 17, 2007. Retrieved July 1, 2008.</ref>\n\nAdditionally, some patients in some First World countries are finding that insurance either does not cover orthopedic surgery (such as knee or hip replacement) or limits the choice of the facility, surgeon, or prosthetics to be used.\n\nPopular medical travel worldwide destinations include: [[Canada]], [[Cuba]], [[Costa Rica]], [[Ecuador]], [[India]], [[Israel]], [[Jordan]], [[Malaysia]], [[Mexico]], [[Singapore]], [[South Korea]], [[Taiwan]], [[Thailand]], [[Turkey]], [[United States]].<ref>[http://www.patientsbeyondborders.com/medical-tourism-statistics-facts \"Patient Beyond Borders, Medical Tourism Facts&Statistics\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426234639/http://www.patientsbeyondborders.com/medical-tourism-statistics-facts |date=2014-04-26 }} Retrieved July 14, 2014</ref>\n\nPopular destinations for cosmetic surgery include: [[Argentina]], [[Bolivia]], [[Brazil]], [[Colombia]], [[Costa Rica]], [[Cuba]], [[Ecuador]], [[Mexico]], [[Turkey]], [[Thailand]] and [[Ukraine]]. According to the \"Sociedad Boliviana de Cirugia Plastica y Reconstructiva\", more than 70% of middle and upper class women in the country have had some form of plastic surgery. Other destination countries include [[Belgium]], [[Poland]], [[Slovakia]] and [[South Africa]].<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/background/healthcare/medicaltourism.html \"Medical tourism: Need surgery, will travel\"] ''CBC News Online'', June 18, 2004. Retrieved September 5, 2006.</ref>\n\nSome people travel for [[assisted reproductive technology|assisted pregnancy]], such as [[in-vitro fertilization]], or [[surrogate pregnancy|surrogacy]],<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Jones CA, Keith LG | year = 2006 | title = Medical tourism and reproductive outsourcing: the dawning of a new paradigm for healthcare | url = | journal = Int J Fertil Womens Med | volume = 51 | issue = | pages = 251\u2013255 }}</ref> or freezing embryos for retro-production.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Jones C | year = 2007 | title = Ethical and legal conundrums of post-modern procreation | url = | journal = Int J Gynaecol Obstet | volume =  | issue = | page =  }}</ref>\n\nHowever, perceptions of medical tourism are not always positive. In places like the US, which has high standards of quality, medical tourism is viewed as risky. In some parts of the world, wider political issues can influence where medical tourists will choose to seek out health care.\n\n[[Medical tourism provider]]s have developed as intermediaries which unite potential medical tourists with surgeons, provider hospitals and other organizations. In some cases, surgeons from the United States have  signed up with medical tourism providers to travel to Mexico  to treat American patients. The hope is that using an American surgeon may alleviate concerns about going outside the country, and persuade self-insured American employers to offer this cost-effective option to their workers as a way to save money while still provide high-quality care.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Galewitz |first1=Phil |title=To Save Money, American Patients And Surgeons Meet In Cancun |url=https://khn.org/news/to-save-money-american-patients-and-surgeons-meet-in-cancun/ |website=Kaiser Health News |publisher=Kaiser Family Foundation |accessdate=14 August 2019|date=2019-08-12 }}</ref> Companies that focus on medical value travel typically provide nurse case managers to assist patients with pre- and post-travel medical issues. They may also help provide resources for follow-up care upon the patient's return.\n\nCircumvention tourism is also an area of medical tourism that has grown. Circumvention tourism is travel in order to access medical services that are legal in the destination country but illegal in the home country. This can include travel for fertility treatments that aren\u2019t yet approved in the home country, abortion, and doctor-assisted suicide.<ref name=\"Circumvention Tourism\">{{cite journal|last1=Cohen|first1=Glenn|title=Circumvention Tourism|journal=Cornell Law Review|date=2012|volume=97|issue=1309}}</ref> Abortion tourism can be found most commonly in Europe, where travel between countries is relatively simple. Ireland and Poland, two European countries with highly restrictive abortion laws, have the highest rates of circumvention tourism. In Poland especially, it is estimated that each year nearly 7,000 women travel to the UK, where abortion services are free through the National Health Service.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Day|first1=Matthew|title=Polish women encouraged to come to UK for 'free abortions' on NHS|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/poland/7441990/Polish-women-encouraged-to-come-to-UK-for-free-abortions-on-NHS.html|accessdate=28 April 2015|agency=The Telegraph|publisher=Telegraph Media Group|date=March 15, 2010}}</ref> There are also efforts being made by independent organizations and doctors, such as with Women on Waves, to help women circumvent draconian laws in order to access medical services. With Women on Waves, the organization uses a mobile clinic aboard a ship to provide medical abortions in international waters, where the law of the country whose flag is flown applies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ship campaigns|url=http://www.womenonwaves.org/en/page/2582/ship-campaigns|website=Women on Waves|publisher=Women on Waves}}</ref>\n\n==International healthcare accreditation==\n{{Main|International healthcare accreditation}}\n\nInternational healthcare accreditation is the process of certifying a level of quality for healthcare providers and programs across multiple countries.  [[List of international healthcare accreditation organizations|International healthcare accreditation organizations]] certify a wide range of healthcare programs such as hospitals, primary care centers, medical transport, and ambulatory care services.<ref>{{citation|title=Joint Commission International Accreditation & Certificationweb |url=http://www.jointcommissioninternational.org/Accreditation-and-Certification-Process/ |publisher=Joint Commission International |accessdate=19 July 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722144022/http://www.jointcommissioninternational.org/Accreditation-and-Certification-Process/ |archivedate=22 July 2011 }}</ref>  There are a number of accreditation schemes available based in a number of different countries around the world.\n\nThe oldest international accrediting body is Accreditation Canada, formerly known as the Canadian Council on Health Services Accreditation,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.accreditation.ca/about-us/history/ |title=Accreditation Canada History |accessdate=June 12, 2012}}</ref> which accredited the Bermuda Hospital Board as soon as 1968.  Since then, it has accredited hospitals and health service organizations in ten other countries.\n[[File:GoldSeal 4color.jpg|alt=JCI Gold Seal, an example of international hospital standard accreditation|thumb|JCI Gold Seal, an example of international hospital standard \naccreditation\n]]\nIn the United States, the accreditation group [[Joint Commission International]] (JCI) was formed in 1994 to provide international clients education and consulting services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ncamss.org/AnnualMtg2009/Dengler%20-%20Joint%20Commission%20History.pdf|title=A Journal Through the History of The Joint Commission|publisher=The Joint Commission|accessdate=2014-04-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413150707/http://www.ncamss.org/AnnualMtg2009/Dengler%20-%20Joint%20Commission%20History.pdf|archive-date=2014-04-13|url-status=dead}}</ref> Many international hospitals today see obtaining international accreditation as a way to attract American patients.<ref>[http://www.medicaltravelauthority.com/Medical-Tourism-Magazine-Issue-2.pdf \"Medical Tourism Magazine\"], Medical Tourism Association, February 2008</ref>\n\nJoint Commission International is a relative of the Joint Commission in the United States. Both are US-style independent private sector not-for-profit organizations that develop nationally and internationally recognized procedures and standards to help improve patient care and safety. They work with hospitals to help them meet Joint Commission standards for patient care and then accredit those hospitals meeting the standards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jointcommission.org/AboutUs/Fact_Sheets/jci_facts.htm |title=Facts about Joint Commission International |publisher=Joint Commission |date=2008-12-11 |accessdate=2010-09-15}}</ref>\n\nA British scheme, QHA Trent Accreditation, is an active independent holistic accreditation scheme, as well as GCR.org which monitors the success metrics and standards of almost 500,000 medical clinics worldwide.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=G-jECQAAQBAJ&pg=PA378&lpg=PA378&dq=qha+trent+accreditation#v=onepage&q=qha%20trent%20accreditation&f=false|title=Handbook on Medical Tourism and Patient Mobility|date=2015|isbn=9781783471195|last1=Lunt|first1=Neil|last2=Horsfall|first2=Daniel|last3=Hanefeld|first3=Johanna}}</ref>\n\nThe different international healthcare accreditation schemes vary in quality, size, cost, intent and the skill and intensity of their marketing. They also vary in terms of cost to hospitals and healthcare institutions making use of them.<ref>[https://archive.is/20130126134030/http://www.imtjonline.com/news/india-accreditation-a-must \"INDIA: Accreditation a must\"], International Medical Travel Journal</ref>\n\nIncreasingly, some hospitals are looking towards dual international accreditation, perhaps having both JCI to cover potential US clientele, and Accreditation Canada or QHA Trent. As a result of competition between clinics for American medical tourists, there have been initiatives to rank hospitals based on patient-reported metrics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldhospitalmonitor.com |title=Home |publisher=World Hospital Monitor |accessdate=2010-09-15}}</ref>\n\n==Risks==\nMedical tourism carries some risks that locally provided medical care either does not carry or carries to a much lesser degree.\n\nSome countries, such as South Africa, or Thailand have very different infectious disease-related epidemiology to Europe and North America. Exposure to diseases without having built up natural immunity can be a hazard for weakened individuals, specifically with respect to gastrointestinal diseases (e.g. [[hepatitis A]], [[amoebic dysentery]], [[paratyphoid]]) which could weaken progress and expose the patient to [[Mosquito-borne disease|mosquito-transmitted diseases]], [[influenza]], and [[tuberculosis]]. However, because in poor tropical nations diseases run the gamut, doctors seem to be more open to the possibility of considering any infectious disease, including [[HIV]], TB, and [[typhoid]], while there are cases in the West where patients were consistently misdiagnosed for years because such diseases are perceived to be \"rare\" in the West.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lungil.org/il/copd/TBMisdiagnosed.asp|title=TB Often Misdiagnosed|publisher=American Lung Association of Illinois|accessdate=2007-03-10 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070301064539/http://www.lungil.org/il/copd/TBMisdiagnosed.asp |archivedate = March 1, 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe quality of post-operative care can also vary dramatically, depending on the hospital and country, and may be different from US or European standards. Also, traveling long distances soon after surgery can increase the risk of complications. Long flights and decreased mobility associated with window seats can predispose one towards developing [[deep vein thrombosis]] and potentially a [[pulmonary embolism]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chestnet.org/accp/article/new-dvt-guidelines-no-evidence-support-economy-class-syndrome |title=New DVT Guidelines: No Evidence to Support \"Economy Class Syndrome\"; Oral Contraceptives, Sitting in a Window Seat, Advanced Age, and Pregnancy Increase DVT Risk in Long-distance Travelers |date=7 February 2012 |publisher=American College of Chest Physicians |accessdate=10 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120209195940/http://www.chestnet.org/accp/article/new-dvt-guidelines-no-evidence-support-economy-class-syndrome |archive-date=9 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Other vacation activities can be problematic as well &mdash; for example, scars may become darker and more noticeable if they are sunburned while healing.<ref>[http://familydoctor.org/familydoctor/en/prevention-wellness/staying-healthy/first-aid/caring-for-your-incision-after-surgery.html \"Caring for Your Incision After Surgery\"], FamilyDoctor.org, ''American Academy of Family Physicians'', December 2010. Retrieved July 23, 2013.</ref>\n\nAlso, health facilities treating medical tourists may lack an adequate complaints policy to deal appropriately and fairly with complaints made by dissatisfied patients.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pat.nhs.uk/downloads/ComplaintsleafletDec2011.pdf |title=Compliments, Comments, Concerns or Complaints |publisher=The Pennine Acute Hospitals |accessdate=2015-01-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150101195543/http://www.pat.nhs.uk/downloads/ComplaintsleafletDec2011.pdf |archive-date=2015-01-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nDifferences in healthcare provider standards around the world have been recognised by the [[World Health Organization]], and in 2004 it launched the [[World Alliance for Patient Safety]]. This body assists hospitals and government around the world in setting patient safety policy and practices that can become particularly relevant when providing medical tourism services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/patientsafety/en/ |title=World Alliance for Patient Safety |publisher=Who.int |date=2010-05-05 |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref>\n\nPatients traveling to countries with less stringent surgical standards may be at higher risk for complications.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cusumano|first=Lucas R.|last2=Tran|first2=Vivy|last3=Tlamsa|first3=Aileen|last4=Chung|first4=Philip|last5=Grossberg|first5=Robert|last6=Weston|first6=Gregory|last7=Sarwar|first7=Uzma N.|date=October 2017|title=Rapidly growing Mycobacterium infections after cosmetic surgery in medical tourists: the Bronx experience and a review of the literature|journal=International Journal of Infectious Diseases |volume=63|pages=1\u20136|doi=10.1016/j.ijid.2017.07.022|issn=1878-3511|pmid=28780185}}</ref> If there are complications, the patient may need to stay in the foreign country for longer than planned or if they have returned home, will not have easy access to follow up care.<ref name=\"Ginger Rough\">{{cite news|url=http://www.azcentral.com/arizonarepublic/news/articles/2009/06/07/20090607rxtourism0607.html?nclick_check=1#reply17699291|title=Globe-trotting to cut down on medical costs|last=Ginger Rough|date=June 7, 2009|work=[[The Arizona Republic]]|accessdate=1 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nPatients sometimes travel to another country to obtain medical procedures that doctors in their home country refuse to perform because they believed that the risks of the procedure outweigh the benefits. Such patients may have difficulty getting insurance (whether public or private) to cover follow up medical costs should the feared complications indeed arise.\n\n===Legal issues===\nReceiving medical care abroad may subject medical tourists to unfamiliar legal issues.<ref name=\"AHC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ahcpub.com/hot_topics/?htid=1&httid=1874 |title=Medical Tourism: Ethical Pitfalls of Seeking Health Care Overseas |publisher=Ahcpub.com |accessdate=2011-10-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707094359/http://www.ahcpub.com/hot_topics/?htid=1&httid=1874 |archive-date=2011-07-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The limited nature of [[litigation]] in various countries is a reason for accessibility of care overseas. While some countries currently presenting themselves as attractive medical tourism destinations provide some form of legal remedies for [[medical malpractice]], these legal avenues may be unappealing to the medical tourist. Should problems arise, patients might not be covered by adequate personal insurance or might be unable to seek compensation via [[malpractice]] lawsuits. Hospitals and/or doctors in some countries may be unable to pay the financial damages awarded by a court to a patient who has sued them, owing to the hospital and/or the doctor not possessing appropriate insurance cover and/or medical indemnity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medicalprotection.org/uk |title=Medical Protection Society &#124; MPS UK |publisher=Medicalprotection.org |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref>\n\nIssues can also arise for patients who seek out services that are illegal in their home country. In this case, some countries have the jurisdiction to prosecute their citizen once they have returned home, or in extreme cases extraterritorially arrest and prosecute.<ref name=\"Circumvention Tourism\"/> In Ireland, especially, in the 1980s-90s there were cases of young rape victims who were banned from traveling to Europe to get legal abortions. Ultimately, Ireland\u2019s Supreme Court overturned the ban; they and many other countries have since created \"right to travel\" amendments.<ref name=\"Circumvention Tourism\"/><ref>{{cite book|last1=Spreng|first1=Jennifer|title=Abortion and Divorce Law in Ireland|date=2004|publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc|location=Jefferson, NC|isbn=978-0786416752|page=150}}</ref>\n\n===Ethical issues===\nThere can be major ethical issues around medical tourism.<ref name=\"AHC\"/> For example, the illegal purchase of organs and tissues for transplantation had been methodically documented and studied in countries such as India,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://future.iftf.org/2006/04/the_dark_side_o.html |title=IFTF's Future Now: The dark side of medical tourism |publisher=Future.iftf.org |date=2006-04-19 |accessdate=2011-10-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929135242/http://future.iftf.org/2006/04/the_dark_side_o.html |archive-date=2011-09-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2008/02/09/MN23UPQ0K.DTL | work=The San Francisco Chronicle | title=Organ-transplant black market thrives in India | first=Anuj | last=Chopra | date=February 9, 2008}}</ref> China,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.epochtimes.com/news/7-5-23/55627.html |title= Transplants and Ethics in San Francisco |publisher=The Epoch Times |date=2007-05-23 |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref><ref name=orgharv>[[David Kilgour]], [[David Matas]] (6 July 2006, revised 31 January 2007)  [http://organharvestinvestigation.net An Independent Investigation into Allegations of Organ Harvesting of Falun Gong Practitioners in China] (free in 22 languages)  organharvestinvestigation.net</ref> Colombia<ref>{{cite journal | author = Lee Mendoza Roger | year = 2010 | title = Colombia's organ trade: Evidence from Bogot\u00e1 and Medell\u00edn | journal = Journal of Public Health | volume = 18 | issue = 4| pages = 375\u2013384 | doi=10.1007/s10389-010-0320-3}}</ref> and the Philippines.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Roger Lee Mendoza|date=2010|title=Price deflation and the underground organ economy in the Philippines|journal=Oxford Journal of Public Health|volume=33 |issue=1 |pages=101\u2013107|url=http://jpubhealth.oxfordjournals.org/content/33/1/101.abstract}}</ref>  The [[Declaration of Istanbul]] distinguishes between ethically problematic \"transplant tourism\" and \"travel for transplantation\".<ref>{{cite journal | author = Participants in the International Summit on Transplant Tourism and Organ Trafficking convened by The Transplantation Society and International Society of Nephrology in Istanbul, Turkey, 30 April to 2 May 2008 | year = 2008| title = The Declaration of Istanbul on Organ Trafficking and Transplant Tourism | doi = 10.1038/ki.2008.388 | pmid = 20142924| journal = Kidney International | volume = 74 | issue = 7| pages = 854\u201359 | pmc = 2813140 }}</ref>\n\nMedical tourism may raise broader ethical issues for the countries in which it is promoted. For example, in India, some argue that a \"policy of 'medical tourism for the classes and health missions for the masses' will lead to a deepening of the inequities\" already embedded in the health care system.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.issuesinmedicalethics.org/132ed042.html|title=Indian Journal of Medical Ethics|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730071321/http://www.issuesinmedicalethics.org/132ed042.html|archive-date=30 July 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> In Thailand, in 2008 it was stated that, \"Doctors in Thailand have become so busy with foreigners that Thai patients are having trouble getting care\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=16735157 |title=Medical Tourism Creates Thai Doctor Shortage |publisher=NPR |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref> Medical tourism centered on new technologies, such as [[stem cell treatments]], is often criticized on grounds of fraud, blatant lack of scientific rationale and patient safety. However, when pioneering advanced technologies, such as providing 'unproven' therapies to patients outside of regular clinical trials, it is often challenging to differentiate between acceptable medical innovation and unacceptable patient exploitation.<ref>{{cite journal|title= Medical innovation versus stem cell tourism|date=2011-10-03 |pmid=19556497 | doi=10.1126/science.1171749 |volume=324 |issue=5935 |journal=Science |pages=1664\u20135 |vauthors=Lindvall O, Hyun I |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/66b5cc03376d042a04f66fee219c5d85b82ff8cf }}</ref><ref>[http://www.isscr.org/clinical_trans/index.cfm ISSCR Guidelines for the Clinical Translation of Stem Cells. 2008] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090603085208/http://www.isscr.org/clinical_trans/index.cfm |date=June 3, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n== Employer-sponsored health care in the US ==\nSome US employers have begun exploring medical travel programs as a way to cut employee [[health care prices in the United States|health care costs]].  Such proposals have raised stormy debates between employers and [[trade union]]s representing workers, with one union stating that it deplored the \"shocking new approach\" of offering employees overseas treatment in return for a share of the company's savings.  The unions also raise the issues of [[legal liability]] should something go wrong, and potential job losses in the US health care industry if treatment is [[outsourcing|outsourced]].<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/11/business/worldbusiness/11health.html Union Disrupts Plan to Send Ailing Workers to India for Cheaper Medical Care], [[The New York Times]]</ref>\n\nEmployers may offer incentives such as paying for air travel and waiving out-of-pocket expenses for care outside of the US. For example, in January 2008, Hannaford Bros., a supermarket chain based in Maine, began paying the entire medical bill for employees to travel to Singapore for hip and knee replacements, including travel for the patient and companion.<ref>McGinley, Laurie,\n[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB120283288380762505 \"Health Matters: The next wave of medical tourists might include you\"], Wall Street Journal, February 16, 2008. Retrieved March 13, 2008.</ref>  Medical travel packages can integrate with all types of [[health insurance]], including limited benefit plans,<ref>\n[http://www.bizjournals.com/houston/stories/2004/02/16/focus7.html \"Mini-Meds: Limited benefit plans provide cost-effective compromise\"] Houston Business Journal,</ref> [[preferred provider organization]]s and [[High Deductible Health Plan|high deductible health plan]]s.\n\nIn 2000, Blue Shield of California began the United States' first cross-border health plan. Patients in California could travel to one of the three certified hospitals in Mexico for treatment under California Blue Shield.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20101229023927/https://www.blueshieldca.com/bsc/newsroom/pr/United_Behavioral_Health.jhtml ]</ref> In 2007, a subsidiary of BlueCross BlueShield of South Carolina, Companion Global Healthcare, teamed up with hospitals in Thailand, Singapore, Turkey, Ireland, Costa Rica and India.<ref>Bruce Einhorn, [http://www.businessweek.com/magazine/content/08_12/b4076036777780.htm?chan=rss_topStories_ssi_5 \"Outsourcing the Patients\"], [[BusinessWeek]], March 13, 2008</ref> A 2008 article in ''[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]]'' discusses the globalization of healthcare and describes how various players in the US healthcare market have begun to explore it.<ref>Greg Lindsay,[http://www.fastcompany.com/magazine/125/medical-leave.html \"Medical Leave\"] Fast Company, May 2008. Retrieved October 15, 2008.</ref>\n\n== Destinations ==\n\n<!-- please leave this section as alphabetical -->\n\n===Africa and the Middle East===\n<!-- do not add a country subsection unless you can cite a reliable source.  Medical tourism blogs are not reliable sources. -->\n\n====South Africa====\n[[Healthcare in South Africa|South Africa]] is the first country in [[Africa]] to emerge as a medical tourism destination.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaclubsouthafrica.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1274:sa-medical-tourism-060809&catid=50:visitnews&Itemid=117 |title=: Medical tourism in SA |publisher=Mediaclubsouthafrica.com |date=2009-08-06 |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref>\n\n====Tunisia====\nOn the African scale, Tunisia ranks second in the field of health tourism. It is also named the world's second best thalassotherapy destination, behind France. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.webmanagercenter.com/2018/03/09/417123/tourisme-medical-la-tunisie-est-classee-au-2eme-rang-en-afrique/ |title=: Tourisme m\u00e9dical : La Tunisie est class\u00e9e au 2\u00e8me rang en Afrique |publisher=www.webmanagercenter.com |date=2018-03-09 |accessdate=2020-02-05}}</ref>\n\n====Jordan====\n[[Jordan]], through their Private Hospitals Association, attracted 250,000 international patients accompanied by more than 500,000 companions in 2012, with total revenues exceeding 1B US$.<ref name=\"JordanAward\">{{cite web|url=http://awards.imtj.com/results |title=IMTJ MEDICAL TRAVEL AWARDS 2014 |accessdate=2014-04-25}}</ref> Jordan won the Medical Destination of the year award in 2014 in the IMTJ Medical Travel Awards.<ref name=\"JordanAward\"/>\n\n====Israel====\n{{See also|Medical tourism in Israel}}\n[[Healthcare in Israel|Israel]] is a popular destination for medical tourism.<ref name=\"Haaretz\">[http://www.haaretz.com/news/national/health-ministry-to-probe-israel-medical-tourism-industry-following-haaretz-expose-1.325424 Health Ministry to probe Israel medical tourism industry following Haaretz expos\u00e9], [[Haaretz]], November 18, 2010</ref> Many medical tourists to Israel come from Europe, particularly the former Soviet Union, as well as the United States, Australia, Cyprus, and South Africa. Medical tourists come to Israel for a variety of surgical procedures and therapies, including bone marrow transplants, heart surgery, and catheterization, oncological and neurological treatments, orthopedic procedures, car accident rehabilitation, and [[in-vitro fertilization]]. Israel's popularity as a destination for medical tourism stems from its status as a developed country with a high-quality level of medical care, while at the same time having lower medical costs than many other developed countries. Israel is particularly popular as a destination for bone marrow transplants among Cypriots, as the procedure is not available in Cyprus, and for orthopedic procedures among Americans, as the cost of orthopedic procedures in Israel is about half that of in the United States. Israel is a particularly popular destination for people seeking IVF treatments. Medical tourists in Israel use both public and private hospitals, and all major Israeli hospitals offer medical tourism packages which typically cost far less than comparable procedures than in facilities elsewhere with a similarly high standard of care. In 2014, it was estimated that roughly 50,000 medical tourists came to Israel annually.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.imtj.com/articles/update-medical-tourism-development-israel/ | title=An overview of medical tourism in Israel &#124; IMTJ}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.timesofisrael.com/israel-ranks-as-a-top-medical-tourism-destination/ | title=Israel ranks high as a medical tourism destination}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=http://www.haaretz.com/israel-news/culture/health/1.631674 | title=Doing Fertility Treatments in Israel: Pros and Cons| newspaper=Haaretz| date=2015-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.zendette.com/2015/04/14/medical-tourism-why-israel/ | title=Medical tourism \u2013 why Israel?| date=2015-04-14}}</ref> There are reports that these medical tourists obtain preferential treatment, to the detriment of local patients.<ref name=\"Haaretz\" /> In addition, some people come to Israel to visit health resorts at the [[Dead Sea]],<ref name=\"Haaretz\"/> and on [[Lake Kinneret]].\n\n====Iran====\nIn 2012, 30,000 people came to [[Healthcare in Iran|Iran]] to receive medical treatment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.farsnews.com/newstext.php?nn=9010171549 |title=Fars News Agency :: Ahmadinejad Stresses Iran's Growing Medical Tourism Industry |publisher=English.farsnews.com |date=2012-01-17 |accessdate=2012-02-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://swap.stanford.edu/20120213085015/http%3A//english.farsnews.com/newstext.php?nn%3D9010171549 |archivedate=2012-02-13 }}</ref>\nIn 2015, it is estimated that between 150,000 and 200,000 health tourists came to Iran, and this figure is expected to rise to 500,000 a year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irna.ir/en/News/81456929/ |title=500,000 health tourists coming to Iran for medical treatment |website=Irna.ir |date= |accessdate=2017-01-08}}</ref>\n\n====United Arab Emirates====\nUnited Arab Emirates, especially Dubai, Abu Dhabi, Ras Al Khaimah is a popular destination for medical tourism. The Dubai Health authority has been spearheading medical tourism into UAE, especially Dubai. However, hospitals providing medical tourism are spread all over the seven emirates. UAE has the distinction of having the maximum number of JCI accredited hospitals (under various heads).<ref>https://www.jointcommissioninternational.org/about-jci/jci-accredited-organizations/?c=United%20Arab%20Emirates</ref> UAE has inbound medical tourism as well as people going out for medical treatment. The inbound tourism usually is from African countries like Nigeria, Kenya, Uganda, Rwanda, etc. The outbound can be categorised into two segments - the local population (citizens of UAE) and the expats. The locals prefer to go to European destinations like the U.K., Germany etc. The expats prefer to go back to their home countries for treatment.\n\n===Americas===\n<!-- do not add a country subsection unless you can cite a reliable source.  Medical tourism blogs are not reliable sources. -->\n\n====Brazil====\nIn [[Healthcare in Brazil|Brazil]], [[Albert Einstein Hospital]] in S\u00e3o Paulo was the first JCI-accredited facility outside of the US,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/hospital-israelita-albert-einstein-becomes-first-hospital-accredited-by-joint-commission-international-72671117.html |title=Hospital Israelita Albert Einstein Becomes First Hospital Accredited by Joint Commission International |accessdate=2014-11-12 |format=Blog |publisher=PR Newswire}}</ref> and more than a dozen Brazilian medical facilities have since been similarly accredited.<ref name=\"JCI\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jointcommissioninternational.org/JCI-Accredited-Organizations/ |title=(JCI) Accredited Organizations |publisher=Joint Commission International |accessdate=2011-10-29 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/69sdmHwPX?url=http://www.jointcommissioninternational.org/JCI-Accredited-Organizations/ |archive-date=2012-08-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n====Mexico====\n\nMexico has 98 hospitals accredited by the country\u2019s Federal Health Ministry and seven hospitals which are JCI-accredited. Mexico is most reputed for advanced care in dentistry and cosmetic surgery. Medical care in Mexico saves a patient 40% to 65% compared to the cost of similar services in the US.\n\n====Canada====\nIn comparison to US health costs, patients can save 30 to 60 percent on health costs in [[Healthcare in Canada|Canada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.deloitte.com/content/dam/Deloitte/ca/Documents/life-sciences-health-care/ca-en-health-care-life-sciences-evolving-medical-tourism-exploring-a-new-frontier.pdf |title=Evolving medical tourism in Canada |website=Deloitte.com |accessdate=2017-01-08}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1990s, Americans illegally using counterfeit, borrowed, or fraudulently obtained Canadian health insurance cards to obtain free healthcare in Canada became a serious issue due to the high costs it imposed.<ref>{{cite news|last=Farnsworth |first=Clyde H. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/12/20/world/americans-filching-free-health-care-in-canada.html?pagewanted=all |title=Americans Filching Free Health Care in Canada |location=Ontario (Canada); Canada; United States |website=NYTimes.com |date=1993-12-20 |accessdate=2017-01-08}}</ref>\n\n====Costa Rica====\nIn Costa Rica, there are two [[Joint Commission on Accreditation of Healthcare Organizations#International accreditation|Joint Commission International]] accredited (JCI) hospitals. Both are in San Jose, Costa Rica. When the World Health Organization (WHO) ranked the world's health systems in the year 2000, Costa Rica was ranked as no. 26, which was higher than the US, and together with Dominica it dominated the list amongst the Central American countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imtj.com/news/?entryid82=290909&source=email&campaign=imtj_news_110527 |title=South Korea wants to expand medical tourism beyond cosmetic surgery |publisher=Imtj.com |date=2009-05-08 |accessdate=2011-10-29}}</ref>\n\nThe Deloitte Center for Health Solutions in 2008 reported a cost savings average of between 30-70 percent of US prices.<ref>[http://www.deloitte.com/assets/Dcom-Croatia/Local%20Assets/Documents/hr_Medical_tourism(3).pdf Medical Tourism Consumers in Search of Value] 2008 Deloitte Development LLC</ref> In 2019 a knee operation in [[Clinica Biblica]]  which would have cost around $44,000 in the USA cost $12,200.<ref>{{cite news |title=I had my misgivings about going abroad for surgery |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-47704954 |accessdate=7 April 2019 |publisher=BBC |date=28 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Cayman Islands====\n{{main|Health City Cayman Islands}}\n\n====Cuba====\n{{main|Health care in Cuba#Health tourism and pharmaceutics}}\n\n====United States====\n{{Main|Health care in the United States}}\nA report of [[McKinsey and Co.]] from 2008 found that between 60,000 and 85,000 medical tourists were traveling worldwide for the purpose of receiving in-patient medical care.<ref name=Forbes08>{{cite news |author=Allison Van Dusen |title=U.S. Hospitals Worth The Trip |url=https://www.forbes.com/2008/05/25/health-hospitals-care-forbeslife-cx_avd_outsourcing08_0529healthoutsourcing.html |quote=It narrowly defined medical travelers as only those whose primary and explicit purpose in traveling was to obtain in-patient medical treatment in a foreign country, putting the total number of travelers at 60,000 to 85,000 per year. |newspaper=[[Forbes]] |date=May 29, 2008 |accessdate=2012-09-17 }}</ref> Some have estimated that 750,000 American medical tourists traveled from the United States to other countries in 2007 (up from 500,000 in 2006).<ref name=Hansen08>Fred Hansen, [http://web.mnstate.edu/robertsb/390/A%20revolution%20in%20healthcare%20Medicine%20meets%20the%20marketplace.pdf], [[Institute of Public Affairs]] review article (January 2008).</ref> According to the McKinsey and Co Report [http://www.heal-wheel-india.com/white-pappers/McKinsey-Report-Medical-Travel.pdf (report)], 45% of North American medical tourists travel to Asia, 26% go to Latin America, 2% go to the Middle East, and 27% travel to another country in North America. None travel to Europe. \n\nThe availability of advanced medical technology and sophisticated training of physicians are cited as driving motivators for growth in foreigners traveling to the US for medical care,<ref name=Forbes08/> whereas the low costs for hospital stays and major/complex procedures at Western-accredited medical facilities abroad are cited as major motivators for American travelers.<ref name=Hansen08/> Also, the decline in [[U.S. currency#International use|value of the US dollar]] between 2007 and 2013 used to offer additional incentives for foreign travel to the US, although cost differences between the US and many locations in Asia are larger than any currency fluctuations.\n\nSeveral major medical centers and teaching hospitals offer international patient centers that cater to patients from foreign countries who seek medical treatment in the US.<ref>[http://stanfordhospital.org/forPatients/patientServices/internationalMedicalServices.html International Medical Services] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612212550/http://stanfordhospital.org/forPatients/patientServices/internationalMedicalServices.html |date=2010-06-12 }}, [[Stanford Hospital|Stanford Hospital & Clinics]]</ref> Many of these organizations offer service coordinators to assist international patients with arrangements for medical care, accommodations, finances and transportation including [[air ambulance]] services.\n\n===Asia and the Pacific Islands===\n<!-- do not add a country subsection unless you can cite a reliable source.  Medical tourism blogs are not reliable sources. -->\n\n====China====\n{{Main|Healthcare in China}}\n[[Ctrip]]'s 2016 Online Medical Tourism Report indicates that the number of travelers who enroll in the oversea medical tourism through its platform increased fivefold over the previous year, and more than 500,000 Chinese visitors are expected to go on medical tourism. The top ten medical tourism destinations are Japan, Korea, the US, Taiwan, Germany, Singapore, Malaysia, Sweden, Thailand, and India.<ref name=\"marce\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.marcetable.com/2017/01/29/medical-tourism-2016-report-china/|title=2016 China Medical Tourism Report|date=2017-01-29|website=Marcetable|access-date=2017-02-12}}</ref>  Regular health checks made up the majority share of Chinese medical tourism in 2016, representing over 50% of all medical tourism trips for tourists originating in China.<ref name=\"marce\"/>\n\n====Hong Kong====\nAll twelve of Hong Kong's private hospitals have been surveyed and accredited by the UK's Trent Accreditation Scheme since early 2001.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080227022521/http://www.1stor.co.uk/trentaccreditationscheme.org/news/tasnews6-200110.pdf]</ref>\n\n====India====\n{{Main|Medical tourism in India}}\nMedical tourism is a growing sector in [[Healthcare in India|India]]. India is becoming the 2nd medical tourism destination after Thailand. [[Chennai]] is regarded as \"India's Health City\" as it attracts 45% of health tourists visiting India and 40% of domestic health tourists.\n\nIndia\u2019s medical tourism sector was expected to experience an annual growth rate of 30% from 2012, making it a $2 billion industry by 2015.<ref>[http://www.indianhealthcare.in/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&catid=39%3ANews&id=357%3AINDIAN+MEDICAL+TOURISM+TO+TOUCH+RS+9,500+CRORE+BY+2015:+ASSOCHAM&sectionid=17&Itemid=77 Indian Medical Tourism To Touch Rs 9,500 Crore By 2015], The Economic Times, posted on IndianHealthCare.in</ref><ref name=\"MedicalCapitalsPlaceInHistory\">{{cite news\n | last = Hamid\n | first = Zubeda\n | title = The medical capital's place in history\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n | pages =\n | language =\n | date = 20 August 2012\n | url = http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/article3796305.ece\n | accessdate = 15 Sep 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, the [[Government of India|Indian government]] made it easier for foreigners to receive medical treatment without necessarily applying for a medical visa. These initiatives by Indian government will help Medical Tourism market to reach around $9 Billion in 2020. Furthermore the major reason for foreign tourist to choose India is because, It boasts 38 [[List of hospitals in India|hospitals]] accredited by the [[Joint Commission|Joint Commission International]].\n<ref name=\"India\u2019s Medical Tourism Market Could Reach $9 Billion Next Year Buoyed By Low Cost, High Quality Service\">{{cite news\n | last = Palash\n | first = Ghosh\n | title = India's Medical Tourism Market\n | newspaper = International business times\n | pages = Business\n | language = English\n | date = 26 November 2019\n | url = https://www.ibtimes.com/indias-medical-tourism-market-could-reach-9-billion-next-year-buoyed-low-cost-high-2874034\n | accessdate = 9 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs medical treatment costs in the developed world balloon\u2014with the United States leading the way\u2014more and more Westerners are finding the prospect of international travel for medical care increasingly appealing.  An estimated 150,000 of these travel to India for low-priced healthcare procedures every year. \n\nIndia is increasingly becoming popular with Africans seeking medical treatment overseas, because of it boast highly qualified doctors and [[State of the art|state-of-the-art equipment]], and the treatments are approved by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) and the [[Food and Drug Administration|US Food and Drug Administration]].\n<ref name=\"India\u2019s medical tourism gets Africans\u2019 attention\">\n{{cite news|url=https://www.un.org/africarenewal/magazine/december-2016-march-2017/india%E2%80%99s-medical-tourism-gets-africans%E2%80%99-attention|title=India's medical tourism|last=Pavithra|first=rao|date=26 March 2017|newspaper=Africa Renewal|accessdate=10 December 2019|pages=Health & Well being|language=English}}</ref> Many patients from [[Africa]] prefer Apollo & Medobal [[Healthcare in India|healthcare]], which are headquartered in [[Chennai]] in India\u2019s state of Tamil Nadu. [[Cosmetic surgery]], [[bariatric surgery]], [[Knee Cap|knee cap replacements]], [[Liver transplantation|liver transplants]], and [[Management of cancer|cancer treatments]] are some of the most sought out medical tourism procedures chosen by foreigners.\n\n====Malaysia====\n{{Main|Medical tourism in Malaysia}}The majority of the foreign patients seeking medical treatments in Malaysia are from Indonesia, with smaller numbers of foreign patients coming from India, Singapore, Japan, Australia, Europe, the USA and the Middle East. In 2008, Indonesians comprised 75% of all foreign patients receiving care in Malaysia; Europeans, 3%; Japanese, 3%; Singaporeans, 1% and citizens from Middle Eastern countries, 1%. By 2011, Indonesians comprised 57% of all foreign patients in Malaysia as the number of patients of other nationalities grew.\n\nHealth insurance companies in Singapore have recently permitted their policyholders to be treated in Malaysia where services are cheaper than in Singapore.\n\n====New Zealand====\n{{Main|Health care in New Zealand}}\nIn 2008, it was estimated that on average New Zealand's surgical costs are around 15 to 20% the cost of the same surgical procedure in the USA.<ref name=\"Eleanor Black Watkin\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/07/03/AR2008070303532_pf.html|title=One Company With an Eye on U.S. Customers|last=Eleanor Black Watkin|date=July 8, 2008|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=1 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Pakistan====\n{{Main|Medical tourism in Pakistan}}\n\n====Singapore====\n[[Healthcare in Singapore|Singapore]] has a dozen hospitals and health centers with JCI accreditation.<ref>[http://www.jointcommissioninternational.org/about-jci/jci-accredited-organizations/?c=SG Joint Commission International (JCI) Accredited Organizations]</ref>  In 2013 medical expenditure generated from medical tourists, mostly from more complex medical procedures, such as heart surgery, was S$832 million, a decline of 25 percent from 2012's S$1.11 billion, as the hospitals faced more competition from neighbouring countries for less complex work.<ref>{{cite news|title=The rise of 5-star hospitals in Singapore|url=http://www.todayonline.com/singapore/hotel-or-hospital|accessdate=10 February 2017|publisher=Today on line|date=8 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Thailand====\n{{Main|Health in Thailand|Tourism in Thailand}}\nForeigners seeking treatment for everything from open-heart surgery to fertility treatments have made [[Thailand]] and its accredited hospitals a popular destination for medical tourism, attracting an estimated 2.81 million patients in 2015, up 10.2 percent.<ref>{{cite news|title=Medical Tourism in Thailand: When Treatment Costs and Starbucks Clash|url=http://www.medicaltourismmag.com/medical-tourism-in-thailand-when-treatment-costs-and-starbucks-clash/|accessdate=14 October 2015|work=Medical Tourism Magazine|date=2015-10-13}}</ref> In 2013, medical tourists spent as much as US$4.7 billion, according to government statistics.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mellor|first1=William|title=Medical Tourists Flock to Thailand Spurring Post-Coup Economy|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-11-18/medical-tourists-flock-to-thailand-spurring-post-coup-economy|accessdate=19 February 2015|work=Bloomberg|date=19 November 2014}}</ref> {{asof|2019}}, with 64 accredited hospitals, Thailand is currently among the top 10 medical tourism destinations in the world. In 2017, Thailand registered 3.3 million visits by foreigners seeking specialised medical treatment. In 2018, this number grew to 3.5 million.<ref name=\"DM-20190212\">{{cite news |last1=Otage |first1=Stephen |title=Uganda: What Uganda Can Learn From Thailand's Medical Tourism |url=https://www.monitor.co.ug/Business/Prosper/What-Uganda-can-learn-Thailand-medical-tourism/688616-4977826-11vacmh/index.html |accessdate=15 February 2019 |work=Daily Monitor |date=12 February 2019 |location=Kampala}}</ref>\n\n===Europe===\n\nIn 2006, it was ruled that under the conditions of the E112 European health scheme, UK health authorities had to pay the bill if one of their patients could establish urgent medical reasons for seeking quicker treatment in another European union country.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thompsons.law.co.uk/clinical-negligence/nhs-waiting-lists-targets.htm |title=NHS Waiting lists: targets and England&Wales comparison |publisher=Thompsons.law.co.uk |date=2006-05-16 |accessdate=2011-10-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202222100/http://www.thompsons.law.co.uk/clinical-negligence/nhs-waiting-lists-targets.htm |archive-date=2014-02-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe European directive on the application of patients\u2019 rights to cross-border healthcare was agreed in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|title=Outcomes in EHCI 2015|url=http://www.healthpowerhouse.com/files/EHCI_2015/EHCI_2015_report.pdf|accessdate=27 January 2016|publisher=Health Consumer Powerhouse|date=26 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606082345/http://www.healthpowerhouse.com/files/EHCI_2015/EHCI_2015_report.pdf|archive-date=6 June 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAn online survey of EU migrants, mostly from Poland, Hungary and Romania, in the UK by the Centre for Population Change in 2019 showed that 46% of them preferred the health system in their country of origin. Only 36% preferred NHS medical treatment, and fewer among those from Western Europe.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Worstall |first1=Tim |title=NHS Not Much Cop Say Those Who've Tried Other Health Care Systems |url=https://www.continentaltelegraph.com/healthcare/nhs-not-much-cop-say-those-whove-tried-other-health-care-systems/ |accessdate=25 March 2019 |publisher=Continental Telegraph |date=22 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Azerbaijan====\nAzerbaijan is a target of health tourists from Iran, Turkey, Georgia and Russia. The Bona Dea International Hospital in Baku was built in 2018 to attract international custom, and has staff from various European countries.<ref>{{cite news |title=Azerbaijan Improves Medical Infrastructure To Lure Health-Conscious Travelers |url=https://caspiannews.com/news-detail/azerbaijan-improves-medical-infrastructure-to-lure-health-conscious-travelers-2018-4-13-15/ |accessdate=7 March 2019 |publisher=Caspian News |date=16 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Croatia====\nCroatia has some claims to be the oldest health tourism destination in Europe, as the [[Hygienic Association of Hvar]] was founded in 1868.<ref>{{cite news |title=History of Tourism from 1868 |url=https://www.total-croatia-news.com/history-2/3218-history-of-tourism-from-1868 |accessdate=27 December 2018 |publisher=Total Croatia |date=24 October 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Finland====\nOn December 9, 2013, the City of Helsinki decided that all minors under the age of 18 and all pregnant mothers living in Helsinki without a valid visa or residence permit are [[Healthcare in Finland|granted the right to the same health care]] and at the same price as all citizens of the city. This service will be available sometime early year 2014. Volunteer doctors of Global Clinic have tried to help these people, for whom only acute care has been available. This means that the [[Healthcare in Finland|Finnish health care system]] is open for all people coming outside of the European Union. The service covers special child health care, maternity clinics and specialist medical care etc. practically for free. It is still unclear if this will increase so called health care tourism, because all you have to do is come to Helsinki as a tourist and let the visa expire.\n\nThe Global Clinic in Turku offers health care for all undocumented immigrants for free.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://yle.fi/uutiset/turku_clinic_offers_health_care_for_undocumented_immigrants/6592725 |title=Turku clinic offers health care for undocumented immigrants |accessdate=2015-01-22}}</ref>\n\n====France====\nBritish NHS patients have been offered treatment in [[Health care in France|France]] to reduce waiting lists for hip, knee and cataract surgery since 2002.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/health/1770348.stm | work=BBC News | title=NHS patients recover after surgery abroad | date=January 19, 2002}}</ref> France is a popular tourist destination but also ranked the world's leading health care system by the [[World Health Organization]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/whr/2000/media_centre/press_release/en/|title=World Health Organization Assesses the World's Health Systems|publisher=|accessdate=13 October 2016}}</ref>  [[European Court of Justice]] said that [[National Health Service (England)]] has to pay back British patients.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/4985190.stm|title=BBC NEWS - Health - NHS told to fund treatment abroad|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe number of patients is growing, and in 2016, France scored # 7 in the Medical Tourism Index.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medicaltourismindex.com/overview/destination-ranking/|title=Medical Tourism Index: Destination Ranking|publisher=|accessdate=13 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Germany====\nIn 2017 there were said to be around 250,000 foreign patients who brought more than 1.2 billion euros income to German hospitals. Some were visitors who fell ill unexpectedly, but it is estimated that more than 40 percent came for planned treatment, the majority from Poland, the Netherlands or France.  There have long been medical tourists from the Middle East. University hospitals and the large municipal clinics, such as [[University Hospital Freiburg]] or [[Vivantes]] in Berlin, are the most popular destinations.<ref>{{cite news |title=Das Riesengesch\u00e4ft mit dem Medizintourismus in Deutschland |url=https://www.dw.com/de/das-riesengesch%C3%A4ft-mit-dem-medizintourismus-in-deutschland/a-42114866 |accessdate=7 March 2019 |publisher=DW |date=11 January 2018}}</ref>  Some require payment in full before they start treatment.<ref>{{cite web |title=Information on Treatment Costs |url=https://www.heidelberg-university-hospital.com/en/finance/ |website=Heildelberg University |accessdate=20 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Hallwang Clinic GmbH]] is said to be the most high profile clinic in the European private cancer industry, centred in Germany, which attracts patients from the US, the UK,  Australia and the Middle East,<ref>{{cite news |title=Cancer crowdfunding 'couldn't save my daughter' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-47442946 |accessdate=6 March 2019 |publisher=BBC |date=6 March 2019}}</ref> offering a variety of different treatments, some of which do not appear to be evidence based; the clinic has been accused of selling false hope.<ref>{{cite news |title=The deadly false hope of German alternative cancer clinics |url=https://sciencebasedmedicine.org/the-deadly-false-hope-of-german-cancer-clinics/ |accessdate=7 March 2019 |publisher=sciencebasedmedicine.org |date=26 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Lithuania====\nHealth Tourism Lithuania, a booking agent, was established in 2018, focusing on the Scandinavian market, but in 2019 in response to longer waiting lists in the [[NHS]] noticed an increase in enquiries about hip replacements, in addition to the existing interest in cosmetic surgery and dentistry from Britons. A hip replacement costs \u00a33,340, about a third of the price of a commercial procedure in the UK.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lithuania to offer Britons cheap surgery as millions stuck on longest NHS waiting list |url=https://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/1132690/NHS-crisis-lithuania-hospitals-Reda-Ambrozaite-HTL-Peter-Gaillard-hip-replacement |accessdate=1 June 2019 |publisher=Express |date=27 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Serbia====\n[[Healthcare in Serbia|Serbia]] has a variety of clinics catering to medical tourists in areas of cosmetic surgery, dental care, fertility treatment and weight loss procedures.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.treatmentabroad.com/destinations/serbia/why-choose-serbia |title=Why choose Serbia for medical tourism |website=Treatmentabroad.com |date=2013-10-08 |accessdate=2017-01-08}}</ref> The country is also a major international hub for gender reassignment surgery.<ref>{{cite news|author=Dan Bilefsky |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/24/world/europe/serbia-becomes-a-hub-for-sex-change-surgery.html |title=Serbia Becomes a Hub for Sex-Change Surgery |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=2012-07-23 |accessdate=2017-01-08}}</ref>\n\n====Russia====\nIn his address to the Federal Assembly of the Russian Federation dated March 1, 2018, Russian President Vladimir Putin stressed the need to develop health care and export services in the field of medicine and tourism.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u041f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u0421\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044e |url=http://www.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/56957 |website=kremlin.ru |accessdate=16 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn accordance with the decree of the President of the Russian Federation of May 7, 2018 \u2116 204 \"on national goals and strategic objectives of the development of the Russian Federation for the period up to 2024\" the volume of exports of medical services by 2024 will have to be $1 billion per year. RAMT in order to implement the Decree of the President of the Russian Federation of 7 May 2018 \u2116 204, the Federal non-profit organization [[Russian Association of Medical Tourism]] was established.\n\n====Turkey====\nThe cost of medical recourses in [[Health care in Turkey|Turkey]] is quite affordable compared to Western European countries. Therefore, thousands of people each year travel to Turkey for their medical treatments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.turkishhealthcaretravelcouncil.org/|title=THTC - Turkish Healthcare Travel Council|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref> Turkey is especially becoming a hub for hair transplant surgery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/bw/articles/2013-05-10/turkeys-thriving-business-in-hair-beard-and-mustache-implants|title=Turkey's Thriving Business in Hair, Beard, and Mustache Implants|author=Sarah A. Topol|work=Businessweek.com|accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref> Almost 178 thousand tourists visited for health purposes in the first six months of 2018.  67% used private hospital, 24% public hospitals and 9% university hospitals.  The Regulation on International Health Tourism and Tourist Health came into force on 13 July 2017. It only applies to those coming specifically for treatment.<ref>{{cite news |title=International Health Tourism in Turkey |url=https://www.lexology.com/library/detail.aspx?g=640bb91d-e7b6-4ef4-bf87-2fd5abf8f69b& |accessdate=13 February 2019 |publisher=Lexology |date=8 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n====United Kingdom====\n\nThe [[National Health Service]] is publicly owned. It attracts medical tourism principally to specialist centres in London. Some private hospitals and clinics in the United Kingdom are medical tourism destinations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imtj.com/articles/2009/the-forgotten-medical-tourism-destination-30026/?locale=en|title=The forgotten medical tourism destination|publisher=|accessdate=9 June 2015|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130126192002/http://www.imtj.com/articles/2009/the-forgotten-medical-tourism-destination-30026/?locale=en|archive-date=26 January 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.imtj.com/news/?EntryId82=285641 |title=UK: New London agency could promote medical tourism |date=20 April 2011}}</ref> UK private hospitals have mandatory registration with the UK's watchdog, the [[Care Quality Commission]]).\n\nThe vast majority of medical tourism in the UK is attracted to London where there are 25 private hospitals and clinics and 12 private patient units run by NHS hospital trusts. American organisations including the [[Cleveland Clinic]], the [[Mayo Clinic]] and [[Ambulatory Surgery International]] have established operations in London.   In 2017 there was a 3% decline in the \u00a31.55 billion market because of fewer clients from the Middle East, who perceive London as expensive. Overseas patients coming to London are now more likely to be looking for cancer treatment than orthopaedics. Income for NHS providers rose by 9% in 2018-9, pushing the [[Royal Marsden]] nearer the 50% statutory limit.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cancer care becomes biggest earner for London's private hospitals |url=https://www.ft.com/content/befcda6c-2b91-11e9-a5ab-ff8ef2b976c7 |accessdate=19 March 2019 |publisher=Financial Times |date=8 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n=====Abuse=====\nIt is alleged that health tourists in the UK often target the NHS for its free-at-the-point-of-care treatment, allegedly costing the NHS up to \u00a3200 million.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://fullfact.org/health/costs_health_tourism-37227|title= Health tourists: How much do they cost and who pays? - Full Fact|date=6 September 2015}}</ref>  A study in 2013 concluded that the UK was a net exporter of medical tourists, with 63,000 UK residents travelling abroad for treatment and about 52,000 patients getting treatment in UK.  Medical tourists treated as private patients by NHS trusts are more profitable than UK private patients, yielding close to a quarter of the revenue from only seven percent of volume of cases.  UK dental patients largely go to Hungary and Poland. Fertility tourists mostly travel to Eastern Europe, Cyprus and Spain.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hannefeld|first1=Johanna|last2=Horsfall|first2=Daniel|last3=Lunt|first3=Neil|last4=Smith|first4=Richard|title=Medical Tourism: A Cost or Benefit to the NHS?|journal=PLOS ONE|date=24 October 2013|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0070406|pmid=24204556|pmc=3812100|volume=8|issue=10|pages=e70406|bibcode=2013PLoSO...870406H}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2015 immigration officers from the [[Border Force]] were stationed in [[St George's University Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust]] to train staff to identify \"potentially chargeable patients\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Immigration officers at London trust for patient charging pilot|url=http://www.lgcplus.com/news/health/social-care/immigration-officers-at-london-trust-for-patient-charging-pilot/5087970.article|accessdate=24 September 2015|publisher=Local Government Chronicle|date=20 July 2015}}</ref>  In October 2016 the trust announced that it planned to require photo identity papers or proof of their right to remain in the UK such as asylum status or a visa for pregnant women. Those not able to provide satisfactory documents would be sent to the trust's overseas patient team \"for specialist document screening, in liaison with the [[UK Border Agency]] and the Home Office.\u201d  It was estimated that \u00a34.6 million a year was spent on care for ineligible patients.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pregnant women could need photo ID to get maternity care as St George's Hospital in Tooting cracks down on NHS tourism|url=http://www.richmondandtwickenhamtimes.co.uk/news/14794980.Pregnant_women_could_need_photo_ID_to_get_maternity_care_at_hospital/|accessdate=29 October 2016|publisher=Richmond and Twickenham Times|date=11 October 2016}}</ref> A pilot scheme to check whether patients were entitled to free NHS care in 18 [[NHS trusts]],  11 in London, for two months in 2017 asked 8,894 people for two forms of ID prior to non-emergency care. Only 50 were not eligible for free NHS treatment. Campaigners claimed this was \u201cpart of the Government\u2019s hostile environment policy\u201d, and that in [[Newham University Hospital|Newham hospital]] \"you will see huge signs saying you may not be eligible for free NHS treatment\".<ref>{{cite news|title=8,900 checks on NHS 'health tourists' find just 50 liable to pay|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/health/8900-checks-on-nhs-health-tourists-find-just-50-liable-to-pay-a3850121.html|accessdate=30 May 2018|publisher=Evening Standard|date=29 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe bills issued to patients thought to be ineligible far exceed the sums actually collected.  Most trusts do not have dedicated staff for the task. Ineligible patients generally live overseas, many have no money, and some demonstrate that they were eligible for free treatment after invoices have been issued. <ref>{{cite news |title=Trusts missing out on tens of millions from overseas patients |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/finance-and-efficiency/trusts-missing-out-on-tens-of-millions-from-overseas-patients/7026384.article |accessdate=9 January 2020 |publisher=Health Service Journal |date=19 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nSee also [[Immigration health surcharge]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Medicine}}\n* [[Wellness tourism]]\n*[[Consumer import of prescription drugs]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikivoyage|Medical tourism}}<!-- PLEASE do not add commercial links, or links to medical tourism companies here -->\n\n* [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/11/02/AR2006110200728_pf.html Businesses May Move Health Care Overseas (Washington Post)]\n* [http://www.cbc.ca/news2/background/healthcare/medicaltourism.html CBC News on \"Medical tourism: Need surgery, will travel\"]\n* [http://abcnews.go.com/Business/IndustryInfo/story?id=2320839&page=1 A Cut Below: Americans Look Abroad for Health Care (ABC News)]\n* [http://www.cbsnews.com/video/watch/?id=781417n|Thailand's Medical Tourism, 60 Minutes (CBS News)]\n\n{{Tourism}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Medical Tourism}}\n[[Category:Medical tourism| ]]\n", "name_user": "CrashClubMedia", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTurkey", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medical_tourism"}
{"title_page": "LGBT rights in the Federated States of Micronesia", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2011}}\n{{Infobox LGBT rights\n| location_header = the Federated States of Micronesia\n| image        = LocationMicronesia.png\n| caption      = [[Federated States of Micronesia]]\n| legal_status = Legal\n| gender_identity_expression = No\n| recognition_of_relationships = No recognition of same-sex couples\n| recognition_of_relationships_restrictions =\n| adoption     = No\n| military     = Has no military\n| discrimination_protections = Sexual orientation protections\n}}\n'''Lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender (LGBT) people in Micronesia''' may face challenges not faced by non-LGBT people. Households headed by same-sex couples are not eligible for the same legal protections available to opposite-sex married couples, as [[same-sex marriage]] and [[civil union]]s are not recognized. Discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation has been illegal since 2018.\n\nThe [[Federated States of Micronesia]] encompasses more than 600 islands and about 100,000 people. The majority of the population identifies as Christian.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newint.org/columns/country/2011/12/01/micronesia]|title=Federated States of Micronesia|website=Newint.org|accessdate=1 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Micronesia signed the \"[[LGBT rights at the United Nations|joint statement on ending acts of violence and related human rights violations based on sexual orientation and gender identity]]\" at the [[United Nations]], condemning violence and discrimination against LGBT people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://geneva.usmission.gov/2011/03/22/lgbtrights/ |title=Over 80 Nations Support Statement at Human Rights Council on LGBT Rights \u00bb US Mission Geneva |publisher=Geneva.usmission.gov |date= }}</ref>\n\n==Law regarding same-sex sexual activity==\nSame-sex sexual activity is legal.<ref name=\"ILGA 2013\">{{cite web|url=http://old.ilga.org/Statehomophobia/ILGA_State_Sponsored_Homophobia_2013.pdf |format=PDF |title=State-Sponsored Homophobia |website=Old.ilga.org |accessdate=2016-03-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6IEmVxpKn?url=http://old.ilga.org/Statehomophobia/ILGA_State_Sponsored_Homophobia_2013.pdf |archivedate=19 July 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nfi.net/downloads/APCOM/Pacific%20MSM_APCOM_Aug07.pdf |format=PDF |title=A report on MSM and the Pacific REgion |website=Nfi.net |accessdate=2016-03-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310190346/http://www.nfi.net/downloads/APCOM/Pacific%20MSM_APCOM_Aug07.pdf |archive-date=10 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The age of consent is 14, regardless of gender and sexual orientation.\n\n==Recognition of same-sex relationships==\nThe Federated States of Micronesia does not recognise same-sex unions in any form.\n\nThe marriage laws in [[Kosrae]] assume the partners to be of the opposite sex.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arc-international.net/global-advocacy/universal-periodic-review/m/federated-states-of-micronesia-cycle-2/|title=Universal Periodic Review|website=ARC International|accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref> Section 16.101 states: \"A marriage performed in the State is valid, if: (a) The male at the time of marriage is at least eighteen years of age and the female at least sixteen years of age, and, if the female is less than eighteen years of age, the marriage has the consent of at least one of the female's parents or her guardian; [...]\".{{efn|In [[Kosraean language|Kosraean]]: {{lang|kos|Pahyuck se oreklac ke State ac akihlenyuck, efin: (a) Mukul se ke pacl in pahyuck an year singucul alkosr matwac ac muhtwacn sacn tiac srihk liki year singucul ohnkohsr matwacl, ac, efin muhtwacn sacn srihk liki year singucul alkosr, pahyuck sacn oasr inseselac luhn sie sin pahpah kuh ninac kuh mwet karihngihn muhtwacn sacn; [...].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kosraestatejudiciary.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Kosrae-State-Code-Kosrae-Version-2012.htm#_Toc333405284|title=Enenuh luhn inseselac inmahsrlo in pahyuck|work=kosraestatejudiciary.com|language=kos}}</ref>}}}}\n\nSimilar language is found in the Chuuk State Code. The Constitution of Pohnpei does not address marriage, but its section on \"family obligations\" states: \"To strengthen and retain good family relations in Pohnpei, as needed, this Constitution recognizes and protects the responsibility and authority of parents over their children\".{{efn|In [[Pohnpeian language|Pohnpeian]]: {{lang|pon|Pwehn kakehlaka oh kolokol onepek mwhau oh wahu penehn nan peneinei kan en Weipokon en Pohnpei, nin duwen ahnepetail, Poahsoan en Kosonned wet pohnese oh wauneki manaman oh pwukoah me sahm akan oh ihn akan akneki ong neirail serihkan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dlib.vanuatu.usp.ac.fj/library/Paclaw/FSM/Code%20of%20the%20State%20of%20Pohnpei/Digital%20Code/Constitution/Pohnpeian%20Version.htm|title=Poahsoan en Kosonned en Weipokon en Pohnpei|work=dlib.vanuatu.usp.ac.fj|language=pon}}</ref>}}}}\n\n==Discrimination protections==\nThe Federated States of Micronesia has an anti-discrimination law that includes sexual orientation, but not gender identity or intersex status. This means gay, lesbian and bisexual people are protected from discrimination in employment, education, health care and other areas of public life, but not transgender people. According to a 2015 write-up from the [[United States Department of State]], \"there were no reports of societal violence or discrimination against homosexuals or against persons with HIV/AIDS.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2001-2009.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2007/100529.htm|title=Micronesia, Federated States of|work=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Micronesia received recommendations from five countries to prohibit discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation and gender identity.<ref name=\"star\"/> In November 2018, the [[Congress of the Federated States of Micronesia|Micronesian Congress]] passed ''C.B. 20-258'', which updated the country's anti-discrimination law to include sexual orientation.<ref>[https://www.cfsm.fm/ifile/Acts/ACT_20-150_JACK.pdf An Act TO AMEND SECTION 107 OF TITLE 1 OF THE CODE OF THE FEDERATED STATES OF MICRONESIA (ANNOTATED), FOR THE PURPOSE OF PROHIBITING DISCRIMINATION BASED ON SEXUAL ORIENTATION, AND FOR OTHER PURPOSES]</ref> The bill, introduced by Speaker [[Wesley Simina]], was supported by three of the four states ([[Chuuk State|Chuuk]], [[Pohnpei State|Pohnpei]], and [[Yap State|Yap]], but opposed by [[Kosrae State|Kosrae]]).\n\nSection 107 of Chapter 1 of the Code of the Federated States of Micronesia reads:<ref>[https://www.cfsm.fm/ifile/20%20congress/BILLS/CB_20-258.pdf C.B. NO. 20-258]</ref>\n:Section 107. Discrimination on account of race, sex, sexual orientation, language, or religion; Equal protection.\n::No law shall be enacted which discriminates against any person on account of race, sex, sexual orientation, language, or religion, nor shall the equal protection of the laws be denied.\n\n==Gender identity and expression==\nMicronesia does not provide any administrative or legal procedures allowing transgender people to have their identified gender recognised in official documents.<ref name=\"star\"/>\n\nAccording to 2017 estimates from [[Joint United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS|UNAIDS]], about 4.2% of the Micronesian transgender population was HIV-positive.<ref name=\"unaids\"/>\n\n==Military service==\nCurrently, there is no active military for the Federated States of Micronesia, though should such a need arise, the [[United States]] is responsible for its defense per mutual agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2137.html?countryName=Micronesia,%20Federated%20States%20of&countryCode=fm&regionCode=au&#fm|title=The World Factbook|website=Cia.gov|accessdate=27 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308041146/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2137.html?countryName=Micronesia,%20Federated%20States%20of&countryCode=fm&regionCode=au&#fm|archive-date=8 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Living conditions==\n===History===\nIn 1989, an anthropologist recorded a case of a young girl on the island of [[Pohnpei]] named Maria who exhibited the habits of a boy and would go walking about at night looking for girls. Family and neighbors held a meeting to discuss the matter, and decided to hold a feast where they would publicly name her a boy. Her hair was cut and she was presented with male clothing, and finally was renamed Mario.<ref name=\"studies\">Zimmermann, Bonnie (2015) ''Encyclopedia of Lesbian Histories and Cultures'', Routledge</ref>\n\nThe islands of [[Chuuk State|Chuuk]] have an indigenous term that refers to a traditional third gender alongside male and female: {{lang|chk|wininmw\u00e1\u00e1n}}.<ref name=\"studies\"/>\n\nIn December 2018, the country's first pride event and parade took place in the state of [[Pohnpei]].<ref>[https://www.gaystarnews.com/article/micronesia-senator-wants-to-ban-trans-people-working-for-government/#gs.aGXRfA4 Micronesia senator wants to ban trans people working for government]</ref>\n\n===Societal opinions===\nMicronesian society tends to be conservative and the LGBT community remains discreet in general. Open displays of affection between same-sex partners may offend.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://travel.state.gov/content/travel/csi_repository/csi_landing/csi_catalog/fsm.html|title=Local Laws & Special Circumstances of Federated States of Micronesia|website=travel.state.gov|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref> Debates and discussions surrounding LGBT rights tend to be \"well off the radar\".<ref name=\"star\">[http://www.starobserver.com.au/news/international-news-news/micronesia-a-diverse-region-with-diverse-lgbti-laws/143887 MICRONESIA: A DIVERSE REGION WITH DIVERSE LGBTI LAWS]</ref>\n\nThe Human Truth Foundation has listed Micronesia at rank 90 for LGBT rights. This was similar to other Pacific nations, such as [[Palau]] (86), [[Nauru]] (87) and the [[Marshall Islands]] (88).<ref>[http://www.humantruth.info/lgbt_rights_across_the_world.html LGBT Rights Across the World, Which are the Best and Worst Countries?]</ref>\n\nIn 2006, an [[evangelicalism|evangelical]] pastor from [[The Salvation Army]] serving as a pastor in Micronesia decried [[homophobia]] and [[conversion therapy]] and stated his belief that [[Biology and sexual orientation|sexual orientation was predetermined]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.micsem.org/pubs/counselor/frames/homosexualityfr.htm|title=Homosexuality in Micronesia|website=Micsem.org|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\nAccording to 2017 estimates from [[Joint United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS|UNAIDS]], there were about 340 [[men who have sex with men]] (MSM) in the country.<ref name=\"unaids\">[http://www.unaids.org/en/regionscountries/countries/federatedstatesofmicronesia/ Country factsheets: MICRONESIA (FEDERATED STATES OF) 2017]</ref>\n\n==Summary table==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| Same-sex sexual activity legal\n| [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] \n|-\n| Equal age of consent\n| [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] \n|-\n| Anti-discrimination laws in employment only\n| [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 2018)\n|-\n| Anti-discrimination laws in the provision of goods and services\n| [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 2018)\n|-\n| Anti-discrimination laws in all other areas (Incl. indirect discrimination, hate speech)\n| [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 2018)\n|-\n| Same-sex marriages\n| [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]]\n|-\n| Recognition of same-sex couples \n| [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]]\n|-\n| Stepchild adoption by same-sex couples\n| [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]]\n|-\n| Joint adoption by same-sex couples\n| [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]]\n|-\n| LGBT people allowed to serve openly in the military\n| [[List of countries without armed forces#Federated states of Micronesia|Has no military]]\n|-\n| Right to change legal gender\n| [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]]\n|-\n| Access to IVF for lesbians\n| [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]]\n|-\n| Commercial surrogacy for gay male couples\n| [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]]\n|-\n| [[Men who have sex with men|MSM]]s allowed to donate blood\n| [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]]\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Human rights in the Federated States of Micronesia]]\n* [[LGBT rights in Oceania]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Oceania in topic|LGBT rights in}}\n\n[[Category:LGBT in the Federated States of Micronesia]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights by country|Micronesia]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights in Oceania|Micronesia]]\n[[Category:Human rights in the Federated States of Micronesia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2011}}\n{{Infobox LGBT rights\n| location_header = the Federated States of Micronesia\n| image        = LocationMicronesia.png\n| caption      = [[Federated States of Micronesia]]\n| legal_status = Legal\n| gender_identity_expression = No\n| recognition_of_relationships = No recognition of same-sex couples\n| recognition_of_relationships_restrictions =\n| adoption     = No\n| military     = Has no military\n| discrimination_protections = Sexual orientation protections\n}}\n'''Lesbian, gay, bisexual and transgender (LGBT) people in Micronesia''' may face challenges not faced by non-LGBT people. Households headed by same-sex couples are not eligible for the same legal protections available to opposite-sex married couples, as [[same-sex marriage]] and [[civil union]]s are not recognized. Discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation has been illegal since 2018.\n\nThe [[Federated States of Micronesia]] encompasses more than 600 islands and about 100,000 people. The majority of the population identifies as Christian.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newint.org/columns/country/2011/12/01/micronesia]|title=Federated States of Micronesia|website=Newint.org|accessdate=1 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Micronesia signed the \"[[LGBT rights at the United Nations|joint statement on ending acts of violence and related human rights violations based on sexual orientation and gender identity]]\" at the [[United Nations]], condemning violence and discrimination against LGBT people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://geneva.usmission.gov/2011/03/22/lgbtrights/ |title=Over 80 Nations Support Statement at Human Rights Council on LGBT Rights \u00bb US Mission Geneva |publisher=Geneva.usmission.gov |date= }}</ref>\n\n==Law regarding same-sex sexual activity==\nSame-sex sexual activity is legal.<ref name=\"ILGA 2013\">{{cite web|url=http://old.ilga.org/Statehomophobia/ILGA_State_Sponsored_Homophobia_2013.pdf |format=PDF |title=State-Sponsored Homophobia |website=Old.ilga.org |accessdate=2016-03-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6IEmVxpKn?url=http://old.ilga.org/Statehomophobia/ILGA_State_Sponsored_Homophobia_2013.pdf |archivedate=19 July 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nfi.net/downloads/APCOM/Pacific%20MSM_APCOM_Aug07.pdf |format=PDF |title=A report on MSM and the Pacific REgion |website=Nfi.net |accessdate=2016-03-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310190346/http://www.nfi.net/downloads/APCOM/Pacific%20MSM_APCOM_Aug07.pdf |archive-date=10 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The age of consent is 14, regardless of gender and sexual orientation.\n\n==Recognition of same-sex relationships==\nThe Federated States of Micronesia does not recognise same-sex unions in any form.\n\nThe marriage laws in [[Kosrae]] assume the partners to be of the opposite sex.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arc-international.net/global-advocacy/universal-periodic-review/m/federated-states-of-micronesia-cycle-2/|title=Universal Periodic Review|website=ARC International|accessdate=23 December 2015}}</ref> Section 16.101 states: \"A marriage performed in the State is valid, if: (a) The male at the time of marriage is at least eighteen years of age and the female at least sixteen years of age, and, if the female is less than eighteen years of age, the marriage has the consent of at least one of the female's parents or her guardian; [...]\".{{efn|In [[Kosraean language|Kosraean]]: {{lang|kos|Pahyuck se oreklac ke State ac akihlenyuck, efin: (a) Mukul se ke pacl in pahyuck an year singucul alkosr matwac ac muhtwacn sacn tiac srihk liki year singucul ohnkohsr matwacl, ac, efin muhtwacn sacn srihk liki year singucul alkosr, pahyuck sacn oasr inseselac luhn sie sin pahpah kuh ninac kuh mwet karihngihn muhtwacn sacn; [...].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kosraestatejudiciary.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Kosrae-State-Code-Kosrae-Version-2012.htm#_Toc333405284|title=Enenuh luhn inseselac inmahsrlo in pahyuck|work=kosraestatejudiciary.com|language=kos}}</ref>}}}}\n\nSimilar language is found in the Chuuk State Code. The Constitution of Pohnpei does not adress marriage, but its section on \"family obligations\" states: \"To strengthen and retain good family relations in Pohnpei, as needed, this Constitution recognizes and protects the responsibility and authority of parents over their children\".{{efn|In [[Pohnpeian language|Pohnpeian]]: {{lang|pon|Pwehn kakehlaka oh kolokol onepek mwhau oh wahu penehn nan peneinei kan en Weipokon en Pohnpei, nin duwen ahnepetail, Poahsoan en Kosonned wet pohnese oh wauneki manaman oh pwukoah me sahm akan oh ihn akan akneki ong neirail serihkan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dlib.vanuatu.usp.ac.fj/library/Paclaw/FSM/Code%20of%20the%20State%20of%20Pohnpei/Digital%20Code/Constitution/Pohnpeian%20Version.htm|title=Poahsoan en Kosonned en Weipokon en Pohnpei|work=dlib.vanuatu.usp.ac.fj|language=pon}}</ref>}}}}\n\n==Discrimination protections==\nThe Federated States of Micronesia has an anti-discrimination law that includes sexual orientation, but not gender identity or intersex status. This means gay, lesbian and bisexual people are protected from discrimination in employment, education, health care and other areas of public life, but not transgender people. According to a 2015 write-up from the [[United States Department of State]], \"there were no reports of societal violence or discrimination against homosexuals or against persons with HIV/AIDS.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://2001-2009.state.gov/g/drl/rls/hrrpt/2007/100529.htm|title=Micronesia, Federated States of|work=U.S. Department of State|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Micronesia received recommendations from five countries to prohibit discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation and gender identity.<ref name=\"star\"/> In November 2018, the [[Congress of the Federated States of Micronesia|Micronesian Congress]] passed ''C.B. 20-258'', which updated the country's anti-discrimination law to include sexual orientation.<ref>[https://www.cfsm.fm/ifile/Acts/ACT_20-150_JACK.pdf An Act TO AMEND SECTION 107 OF TITLE 1 OF THE CODE OF THE FEDERATED STATES OF MICRONESIA (ANNOTATED), FOR THE PURPOSE OF PROHIBITING DISCRIMINATION BASED ON SEXUAL ORIENTATION, AND FOR OTHER PURPOSES]</ref> The bill, introduced by Speaker [[Wesley Simina]], was supported by three of the four states ([[Chuuk State|Chuuk]], [[Pohnpei State|Pohnpei]], and [[Yap State|Yap]], but opposed by [[Kosrae State|Kosrae]]).\n\nSection 107 of Chapter 1 of the Code of the Federated States of Micronesia reads:<ref>[https://www.cfsm.fm/ifile/20%20congress/BILLS/CB_20-258.pdf C.B. NO. 20-258]</ref>\n:Section 107. Discrimination on account of race, sex, sexual orientation, language, or religion; Equal protection.\n::No law shall be enacted which discriminates against any person on account of race, sex, sexual orientation, language, or religion, nor shall the equal protection of the laws be denied.\n\n==Gender identity and expression==\nMicronesia does not provide any administrative or legal procedures allowing transgender people to have their identified gender recognised in official documents.<ref name=\"star\"/>\n\nAccording to 2017 estimates from [[Joint United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS|UNAIDS]], about 4.2% of the Micronesian transgender population was HIV-positive.<ref name=\"unaids\"/>\n\n==Military service==\nCurrently, there is no active military for the Federated States of Micronesia, though should such a need arise, the [[United States]] is responsible for its defense per mutual agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2137.html?countryName=Micronesia,%20Federated%20States%20of&countryCode=fm&regionCode=au&#fm|title=The World Factbook|website=Cia.gov|accessdate=27 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308041146/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2137.html?countryName=Micronesia,%20Federated%20States%20of&countryCode=fm&regionCode=au&#fm|archive-date=8 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Living conditions==\n===History===\nIn 1989, an anthropologist recorded a case of a young girl on the island of [[Pohnpei]] named Maria who exhibited the habits of a boy and would go walking about at night looking for girls. Family and neighbors held a meeting to discuss the matter, and decided to hold a feast where they would publicly name her a boy. Her hair was cut and she was presented with male clothing, and finally was renamed Mario.<ref name=\"studies\">Zimmermann, Bonnie (2015) ''Encyclopedia of Lesbian Histories and Cultures'', Routledge</ref>\n\nThe islands of [[Chuuk State|Chuuk]] have an indigenous term that refers to a traditional third gender alongside male and female: {{lang|chk|wininmw\u00e1\u00e1n}}.<ref name=\"studies\"/>\n\nIn December 2018, the country's first pride event and parade took place in the state of [[Pohnpei]].<ref>[https://www.gaystarnews.com/article/micronesia-senator-wants-to-ban-trans-people-working-for-government/#gs.aGXRfA4 Micronesia senator wants to ban trans people working for government]</ref>\n\n===Societal opinions===\nMicronesian society tends to be conservative and the LGBT community remains discreet in general. Open displays of affection between same-sex partners may offend.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://travel.state.gov/content/travel/csi_repository/csi_landing/csi_catalog/fsm.html|title=Local Laws & Special Circumstances of Federated States of Micronesia|website=travel.state.gov|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref> Debates and discussions surrounding LGBT rights tend to be \"well off the radar\".<ref name=\"star\">[http://www.starobserver.com.au/news/international-news-news/micronesia-a-diverse-region-with-diverse-lgbti-laws/143887 MICRONESIA: A DIVERSE REGION WITH DIVERSE LGBTI LAWS]</ref>\n\nThe Human Truth Foundation has listed Micronesia at rank 90 for LGBT rights. This was similar to other Pacific nations, such as [[Palau]] (86), [[Nauru]] (87) and the [[Marshall Islands]] (88).<ref>[http://www.humantruth.info/lgbt_rights_across_the_world.html LGBT Rights Across the World, Which are the Best and Worst Countries?]</ref>\n\nIn 2006, an [[evangelicalism|evangelical]] pastor from [[The Salvation Army]] serving as a pastor in Micronesia decried [[homophobia]] and [[conversion therapy]] and stated his belief that [[Biology and sexual orientation|sexual orientation was predetermined]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.micsem.org/pubs/counselor/frames/homosexualityfr.htm|title=Homosexuality in Micronesia|website=Micsem.org|accessdate=27 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\nAccording to 2017 estimates from [[Joint United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS|UNAIDS]], there were about 340 [[men who have sex with men]] (MSM) in the country.<ref name=\"unaids\">[http://www.unaids.org/en/regionscountries/countries/federatedstatesofmicronesia/ Country factsheets: MICRONESIA (FEDERATED STATES OF) 2017]</ref>\n\n==Summary table==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| Same-sex sexual activity legal\n| [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] \n|-\n| Equal age of consent\n| [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] \n|-\n| Anti-discrimination laws in employment only\n| [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 2018)\n|-\n| Anti-discrimination laws in the provision of goods and services\n| [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 2018)\n|-\n| Anti-discrimination laws in all other areas (Incl. indirect discrimination, hate speech)\n| [[File:Yes check.svg|15px|Yes]] (Since 2018)\n|-\n| Same-sex marriages\n| [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]]\n|-\n| Recognition of same-sex couples \n| [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]]\n|-\n| Stepchild adoption by same-sex couples\n| [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]]\n|-\n| Joint adoption by same-sex couples\n| [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]]\n|-\n| LGBT people allowed to serve openly in the military\n| [[List of countries without armed forces#Federated states of Micronesia|Has no military]]\n|-\n| Right to change legal gender\n| [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]]\n|-\n| Access to IVF for lesbians\n| [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]]\n|-\n| Commercial surrogacy for gay male couples\n| [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]]\n|-\n| [[Men who have sex with men|MSM]]s allowed to donate blood\n| [[File:X mark.svg|15px|No]]\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Human rights in the Federated States of Micronesia]]\n* [[LGBT rights in Oceania]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Oceania in topic|LGBT rights in}}\n\n[[Category:LGBT in the Federated States of Micronesia]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights by country|Micronesia]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights in Oceania|Micronesia]]\n[[Category:Human rights in the Federated States of Micronesia]]\n", "name_user": "Suecarmol", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRecognition of same-sex relationships:Fix typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LGBT_rights_in_the_Federated_States_of_Micronesia"}
